{"title_page": "Canada lynx", "text_new": "{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{Redirect|Canadian lynx|other species of lynx|Lynx}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Canada lynx\n| image = Canada_lynx_by_Michael_Zahra.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |publisher=[[IUCN]] |author=Vashon, J. |date=2016 |title=''Lynx canadensis'' |page=e.T12518A101138963 |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/12518/101138963 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-2.RLTS.T12518A101138963.en}}</ref>\n| genus = Lynx\n| species = canadensis\n| authority = [[Robert Kerr (writer)|Kerr]], 1792\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = \n{{collapsible list|\n''L. c. canadensis'' (mainland lynx) <small>Kerr, 1792</small><br>\n''L. c. subsolanus'' (Newfoundland lynx) <small>[[Outram Bangs|Bangs]], 1897</small><br>\n''L. c. mollipilosus'' (Arctic lynx) <small>[[Witmer Stone|Stone]], 1900</small>\n}}\n| range_map =CanadaLynx distribution2016.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of Canada lynx (2016)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Canada lynx''' (''Lynx canadensis'') is a medium-sized [[lynx]] native to [[North America]]. It ranges across [[Canada]] and [[Alaska]] extending into the United States portion of the [[Rocky Mountains]]. It is characterized by its long, dense fur, triangular ears with black tufts at the tips, and broad, [[snowshoe]]-like paws. Similar to the [[bobcat]] (''L. rufus''), the hindlimbs are remarkably longer than the forelimbs, so that the back appears to be sloping downward to the front. The lynx is a good swimmer and an agile climber. The Canada lynx stands {{convert|48|\u2013|56|cm|in|abbr=on}} tall at the shoulder and weighs between {{convert|5|and|17|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. This lynx was first [[scientific description|described]] by [[Robert Kerr (writer)|Robert Kerr]] in 1792. Three [[subspecies]] are recognized.\n\nThe Canada lynx is typically [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]] like its primary prey, the [[snowshoe hare]]. The strong dependence of this [[Specialist and generalist species|specialist predator]] on snowshoe hares for food leads to an example of a prey-predator cycle. Canada lynxes respond to the cyclic rises and falls over the years in snowshoe hare populations in Alaska and central Canada\u2014when hares are scarce lynxes tend to move to areas with more hares and tend to not produce litters, and as the numbers of the hare increase, so does the population of the lynx. The lynx waits for the hare in specific trails or \"ambush beds\", then pounces on it and kills it by a bite on its head, throat or the nape of its neck. Individuals of the same sex particularly tend to avoid each other, forming \"intrasexual\" territories. The mating season is roughly a month long (from March to early April). After a gestational period of two to three months, a litter of one to eight kittens is born. Offspring are weaned at 12 weeks.\n\nThis lynx occurs predominantly in dense [[Taiga|boreal forest]]s, and its range heavily coincides with that of the snowshoe hare. Given its abundance throughout its range and no severe threats, this lynx has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]]. This lynx is regularly trapped for the international fur trade in most of Alaska and Canada, but is protected in the southern half of its range due to threats such as habitat loss.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nIn his 1792 work ''The Animal Kingdom'', Scottish scientific writer [[Robert Kerr (writer)|Robert Kerr]] [[Scientific description|described]] a [[Lynx (genus)|lynx]] from Canada, giving it the [[Binomial nomenclature|name]] ''Felis lynx canadensis''.<ref name=\"Kerr1792\">{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=R. |authorlink=Robert Kerr (writer) |title=The Animal Kingdom |date=1792 |publisher=A. Strahan & T. Cadell |location=London |pages=157\u2212158 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/animalkingdomorz00linn/page/157 |chapter=''F. Lynx canadensis''}}</ref> The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]] of the Canada lynx remained disputed through the 20th and early 21st centuries. In 1912, American zoologist [[Gerrit Miller]] placed the Canada lynx under the [[Genus (biology)|genus]] ''Lynx'', with the name ''L. canadensis''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Miller |first1=G. S. Jr. |authorlink = Gerrit Miller  |title=List of North American land mammals in the United States National Museum, 1911 |publisher=United States National Museum |pages=118\u2212121 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinunitedst791912unit#page/118/mode/2up |location = Washington, D.C. |date = 1912}}</ref> Until as late as the early 2000s, scientists were divided on whether ''Lynx'' should be considered a [[Subgenus (biology)|subgenus]] of ''Felis'', or a [[Subfamily (biology)|subfamily]] itself; some even doubted if the Canada lynx should be considered a species on its own.<ref name=Tumlison>{{cite journal |last1=Tumlison |first1=R. |title=''Felis lynx''|journal=[[Mammalian Species]] |date=1987 |issue=269 |pages=1\u20138 |doi=10.2307/3503985 |jstor=3503985}}</ref><ref name=\"lox\">{{cite book |chapter=Lynx |last1=Koehler|first1=G. M.|last2=Aubry|first2=K. B. |title=The Scientific Basis for Conserving Forest Carnivores: American Marten, Fisher, Lynx and Wolverine in the Western United States |date=1994 |publisher=Diane Publishing |location=Colorado |editor1-last=Zielinski |editor1-first=W. J.|editor2-last=Kucerala|editor2-first=T. E. |isbn=978-0-7881-3628-3 |pages=74\u201398 |chapterurl={{Google Books|id=U88sJR0GWtMC|page=74|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Anderson\">{{cite book |last1=Anderson|first1=E. M. |last2=Lovallo |first2=M. J. |chapter=Bobcat and lynx |pages=758\u2013786 |editor1-last=Feldhamer|editor1-first=G. A.|editor2-last=Thompson|editor2-first=B. C.|editor3-last=Chapman |editor3-first=J. A. |title=Wild Mammals of North America: Biology, Management, and Conservation |date=2003 |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-0-8018-7416-1 |edition=2nd|chapterurl={{Google Books|id=-xQalfqP7BcC|page=758|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> American zoologist [[W. Chris Wozencraft|W. C. Wozencraft]] revised the classification of [[Carnivora]] in 2005, and recognized the Canada lynx as a species under ''Lynx'', along with the [[bobcat]] (''L. rufus''), the [[Eurasian lynx]] (''L. lynx'') and the [[Iberian lynx]] (''L. pardinus''). In 2017, the Cat Classification Task Force of the [[IUCN]] Cat Specialist Group revised felid taxonomy, considering the Canada lynx a [[monotypic species]].<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |pages=41\u221242 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref><!--this is not about taxonomy: <ref name=CanLynx>{{cite report |last1=Meaney |first1=C. |last2=Beauvais |first2=G. P. |title=Species assessment for Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') in Wyoming |publisher= [[United States Department of the Interior]], Bureau of Land Management |location=}}</ref> -->\n\nWozencraft recognized three [[subspecies]] of the Canada lynx in ''[[Mammal Species of the World]]'' (2005):<ref name = Catsg2017/><ref name = msw3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |pages=541 |id=14000152 |heading=Species ''Lynx canadensis''}}</ref>\n\n* ''L. c. canadensis'' (mainland lynx) <small>Kerr, 1792</small>: Occurs in the Canadian mainland.\n* ''L. c. mollipilosus'' (Arctic lynx) <small>[[Witmer Stone|Stone]], 1900</small>: Described from the skin and skull of a male lynx killed near [[Wainwright, Alaska|Wainwright]], [[Alaska]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stone |first1=W. |authorlink=Witmer Stone |year=1900 |title=Report on the birds and mammals collected by the McIlhenny Expedition to Pt. Barrow, Alaska |journal=Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia |volume=52 |pages=4\u221249 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofaca52acaduoft/page/48}}</ref>\n* ''L. c. subsolanus'' (Newfoundland lynx) <small>[[Outram Bangs|Bangs]], 1897</small>: Described from a lynx skin and skull collected near [[Codroy]], [[Newfoundland]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bangs |first1=O. |authorlink=Outram Bangs|year=1897 |title=Notes on the lynxes of eastern North America, with descriptions of two new species |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |volume=11 |pages=47\u221251 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio11biol/page/46}}</ref>\n\nA study of the differences (in factors such as coat colour, cranial measurements and weights) between the mainland and Newfoundland forms showed that apart from a few variations (for instance, the Newfoundland lynx features a darker coat than the mainland subspecies), the standard measurements are not significantly distinct. Noting only a few differences between the two forms, the study suggested the Newfoundland lynx to have [[genetic divergence|diverged]] only recently from the mainland form. The lack of appreciable subspecific distinctions led the researchers to doubt the vaidity of the Newfoundland lynx as a separate subspecies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Van Zyll de Jong |first1=C. G. |date=1975 |title=Differentiation of the Canada lynx, ''Felis'' (''Lynx'') ''canadensis subsolana'', in Newfoundland |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |volume=53 |issue=50 |pages=699\u2212705 |doi=10.1139/z75-085}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rueness |first1= E. K. |last2=Stenseth |first2=N. C. |last3=O\u2019Donoghue |first3=M. |last4=Boutin |first4=S. |last5=Ellegren |first5=H. |last6=& Jakobsen |first6=K. S. |date=2003 |title=Ecological and genetic spatial structuring in the Canada lynx |journal=Nature |volume=425 |issue= 6953 |pages=69\u221272|doi=10.1038/nature01942|pmid= 12955141 |bibcode= 2003Natur.425...69R }}</ref> A study in 2019 estimated the Newfoundland lynx to have diverged from the mainland lynx around 20,000 to 33,000 years ago following the [[Last Glacial Period|last glaciation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mer\u00f6ndun |first1=J. |last2=Murray |first2=D. L. |last3=Shafer |first3=A. B. A. |title=Genome\u2010scale sampling suggests cryptic epigenetic structuring and insular divergence in Canada lynx |journal=Molecular Ecology |volume=28 |issue=13 |pages=3186\u20133196 |date=2019 |doi=10.1111/mec.15131|pmid=31087722 }}</ref>\n\n== Evolution ==\n[[File:Lynx issiodorensis 2.JPG|thumb|right|Fossils of the [[Issoire lynx]] (''L. issiodorensis''), which is believed to be the ancestor of the four modern ''Lynx'' species]]\nAccording to a 2006 [[phylogenetic]] study, the ancestor of five felid lineages \u2013 ''Lynx'', ''Leopardus'', ''Puma'', ''Felis'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]'' plus ''[[Otocolobus]]'' \u2013 arrived in North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]] 8.5\u20138 [[Mya (unit)|mya]]. ''Lynx'' diverged from the ''Puma'', ''Felis'' and ''Prionailurus'' plus ''Otocolobus'' lineages around 3.24 mya.<ref name=Johnson2006/> The [[Issoire lynx]] (''L. issiodorensis''), that probably originated in Africa 4 mya and occurred in Europe and northern Asia until it fell to extinction around 1 mya, is believed to be the ancestor of the four modern species of ''Lynx''.<ref name=\"Sunquist\">{{cite book|last1=Sunquist|first1=M.|last2=Sunquist|first2=F.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2002|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|isbn=978-0-226-77999-7|pages=152\u201363|chapter=Canada lynx|chapterurl={{Google Books|id=hFbJWMh9-OAC|pages=152\u2212163 |plainurl=yes}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kurt\u00e9n|first1=B.|title=The lynx from Etouaires, ''Lynx issiodorensis'' (Croizet & Jobert), Late Pliocene|journal=Annales Zoologici Fennici|date=1978|volume=15|issue=4|pages=314\u2013322|jstor=23733663|url=http://www.sekj.org/PDF/anzf15/anzf15-314-322.pdf}}</ref> A 1987 study suggested that the populations of the Eurasian lynx that reached North America 20,000 years ago initially settled in the southern half of the continent, as the northern part was covered by glaciers. The southern populations gradually evolved into the modern bobcat. Later, when the continent was invaded by the Eurasian lynx for a second time, the populations that settled in the northern part of the continent, now devoid of glaciers, evolved into the Canada lynx.<ref name=\"Quinn1987\">{{cite book |last1=Quinn|first1=N.W.S.|last2=Parker|first2=G.|editor1-last=Novak|editor1-first=M.|editor2-last=Baker|editor2-first=J.|editor3-last=Obbard|editor3-first=M.|title= Furbearer Management and Conservation in North America|chapter=Lynx|pages=683\u2013694|date=1987|publisher=Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources|location=Ontario|isbn=978-0-7743-9365-2}}</ref> The 2006 study gave the phylogenetic relationships of the Canada lynx as follows:<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal | author = Johnson, W.E. | author2 = Eizirik, E. | author3 = Pecon-Slattery, J. | author4 = Murphy, W.J. | author5 = Antunes, A. | author6 = Teeling, E. | author7 = O'Brien, S.J. | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1126/science.1122277 | title = The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment | journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]] | volume = 311 | pages = 73\u201377 | pmid = 16400146 | issue = 5757| bibcode = 2006Sci...311...73J | url = https://zenodo.org/record/1230866 }}</ref><ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |author1-link = Lars Werdelin|last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W. E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S. J. |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae)|date=2010|pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142|editor1-last=Macdonald|editor1-first=D.W.|editor2-last=Loveridge|editor2-first=A.J.|title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-923445-5|edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n{{clade|style=font-size:90%;line-height:75%;\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Leopardus]]''\n   |2={{clade\n      |label1=''[[Lynx]]''\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Bobcat]] (''L. rufus'')\n         |2={{clade\n            |1='''Canada lynx''' (''L. canadensis'')\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=[[Iberian lynx]] (''L. pardinus'')\n               |2=[[Eurasian lynx]] (''L. lynx'')\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n         |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Cheetah]] (''Acinonyx jubatus'')\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=[[Cougar]] (''Puma concolor'')\n            |2=[[Jaguarundi]] (''P. yagouaroundi'')\n            }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''  \n            |2={{clade\n               |1=[[Pallas's cat]] (''Otocolobus manul'')\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n     }}\n}}\n}}\n\n== Physical characteristics ==\n[[File:Lynx (5300913523).jpg|thumb|A close facial view of the Canada lynx. The black ear tufts are characteristic of lynxes.]]\n\nThe Canada lynx is a lean, medium-sized cat characterized by its long, dense fur, triangular ears with black tufts at the tips, and broad, [[snowshoe]]-like paws. Similar to the bobcat, the hindlimbs are remarkably longer than the forelimbs, so that the back appears to be sloping downward to the front. The Canada lynx is [[sexually dimorphic]], with males larger and heavier than females. The lynx is between {{convert|73|and|107|cm|in|abbr=on}} in head-and-body length and stands {{convert|48|\u2013|56|cm|in|abbr=on}} tall at the shoulder; females weigh around {{convert|5|\u2013|12|kg|lb|abbr=on}} while males weigh around {{convert|6|\u2013|17|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Sunquist/> Physical proportions do not vary significantly across the range and are probably [[natural selection|naturally selected]] to allow survival on smaller prey.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Werdelin|first1=L.|authorlink=Lars Werdelin|title=The evolution of lynxes|journal=Annales Zoologici Fennici|url=http://lynx.uio.no/lynx/ibelynxco/04_library/4_3_publications/W/Werdelin_1981_Evolution_of_lynxes.pdf|date=1981|volume=18|issue=1|pages=37\u201371|jstor=23734102|access-date=June 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005114343/http://lynx.uio.no/lynx/ibelynxco/04_library/4_3_publications/W/Werdelin_1981_Evolution_of_lynxes.pdf|archive-date=October 5, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Eurasian lynx, that prefers prey the size of a [[roe deer]], is twice the size of the Canada lynx, that feeds primarily on the [[snowshoe hare]].<ref name=Sunquist/> The stubby tail, typical of lynxes, is {{convert|5|\u2013|13|cm|in|abbr=on}} long; while the bobcat's tail is black only in the upper part, the tail of the Canada lynx has a completely black tip.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=146\u2013151|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=146|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> \n\nThe long, dense fur, uniformly coloured with little to no markings except on the underside, insulates the lynx in its frosty habitat. The fur is typically yellowish brown, though in Newfoundland it can vary from brown or buff-gray in spring and summer to a grayish shade with a grizzled appearance in winter; the underparts are white and may have a few dark spots.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|pages=807\u2013808|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=806|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> Although no [[Melanism|melanistic]] or [[Albinism (biology)|albinistic]] forms of the Canada lynx are known, \"blue\" lynxes have been reported in Alaska.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schwarz|first1=E.|title=Blue or dilute mutation in Alaskan lynx|journal=Journal of Mammalogy|date=1938|volume=19|issue=3|page=376|doi=10.1093/jmammal/19.3.376-a}}</ref> The fur is generally shorter in summer than in winter.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reid|first1=F.A.|title=Peterson Field Guide to Mammals of North America|date=2006|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Co.|location=Boston, US|isbn=978-0-547-34553-6|pages=94; 436\u2013437|edition=4th|url={{Google Books|id=jdw0oSIez34C|pg=PA46-IA1|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The backs of the ears are brown with a silvery-gray spot at the centre.<ref name=Tumlison/> Similar to other lynxes, black tufts around {{convert|4|cm|in}} in length emerge from the tips of the ears, which are lined with black fur.<ref name=Hunter/> In winter, the hair on the lower cheek becomes longer, giving the impression of a ruffle covering the throat. There are four nipples.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Nowak/> \n[[File:Canadian lynx by Keith Williams.jpg|thumb|left|As the forelimbs of the Canada lynx are shorter than the hindlimbs, the back appears to be sloping downward toward the front. Note the stubby tail and the dense fur.]]\nThe large, broad paws are covered in long, thick fur and can spread as wide as {{convert|10|cm|in}} to move fast and easily on soft snow.<ref name=Anderson/> The paws of a Canada lynx can support nearly double the weight those of a bobcat can bear before sinking.<ref name=lox/><ref name=Parker>{{cite journal|last1=Parker|first1=G.R.|last2=Maxwell|first2=J.W.|last3=Morton|first3=L.D.|last4=Smith|first4=G.E.J.|title=The ecology of the lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') on Cape Breton Island|journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology|date=1983|volume=61|issue=4|pages=770\u201386|doi=10.1139/z83-102}}</ref> Both species walk with the back foot typically following the front foot, and often do not follow a straight line path. The stride is {{convert|12|\u2013|18|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} for the lynx, while that of the bobcat varies between {{convert|5|and|16|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}}. Canada lynx tracks are generally larger than those of the bobcat; the thicker fur may make the toe pads appear less prominent in the snow. In dirt the tracks of the lynx are {{convert|3|\u2013|3.75|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} long and {{convert|3.5|\u2013|4.5|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} wide, whereas in snow they are bigger ({{convert|4.5|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} long and {{convert|5|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} wide).<ref name = golden/><ref name=\"yukongov\">{{cite report|title=Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') |url=http://www.env.gov.yk.ca/animals-habitat/mammals/documents/Canada_Lynx.pdf |author=Environment Yukon |publisher=Government of Yukon}}</ref> The warm coat, wide paws and long legs serve as adaptations for the lynx to efficiently navigate and hunt in snow.<ref name=lox/>\n[[File:Brooks Range (19) Lynx trail.jpg|thumb|right|Canada lynx tracks in Alaska, with traces of fur]]\nThe Canada lynx has 28 teeth,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burt|first1=W.H.|title=A Field Guide to the Mammals: North America North of Mexico|date=1976|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Co.|location=Boston, US|isbn=978-0-395-91098-6|page=80|edition=3rd|url={{Google Books|id=O3l0WGH4CF4C|page=80|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> same as in other lynxes but unlike other felids that have 30,<ref name=Anderson/> with four long [[canine tooth|canines]] for puncturing and gripping. The lynx can feel where it is biting the prey with its canines because they are heavily laced with nerves. It also has four [[carnassial teeth]] that cut the meat into small pieces. In order for the lynx to use its carnassials, it must chew the meat with its head to its side. There are large spaces between the four canines and the rest of the teeth, and the second upper [[premolar]]s are absent, to ensure that the bite goes as deeply as possible into the prey.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Macdonald|first1=D.|title=The Velvet Claw: A Natural History of the Carnivores|date=1993|publisher=BBC Books|location=New York, US|isbn=978-0-563-20844-0|pages=47\u201350|url=https://archive.org/details/velvetclawnatura00macd|url-access=registration}}</ref> The claws are sharp and fully retractable (capable of being drawn within).<ref name=Tumlison/>\n\nThe Canada lynx can be told apart from the bobcat by its longer ear tufts, broader paws, shorter tail with a fully black tip, longer legs and the fewer markings and grayer shade of the coat.<ref name=Anderson/><ref name=golden>{{cite web|last1=Golden|first1=H.|last2=Krause|first2=T.|title=How to avoid incidental take of lynx while trapping or hunting bobcats and other furbearers|url=http://dnr.wi.gov/topic/trap/documents/avoidlinx.pdf|publisher=United States Fish & Wildlife Service and International Association of Fish and Wildlife Agencies|accessdate=19 July 2014|date=2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Kaufman\">{{cite book|last1=Bowers|first1=N.|last2=Bowers|first2=R.|last3=Kaufman|first3=K.|title=Kaufman Field Guide to Mammals of North America|date=2007|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|location=New York, US|isbn=978-0-618-95188-8|page=138|url={{Google Books|id=vfRgcZIOizEC|page=138|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The bobcat is generally smaller than the Canada lynx, but in areas where they are [[Sympatry|sympatric]] the bobcat tends to be larger and may still be confused with the Canada lynx.<ref name=Hunter/> The [[caracal]] resembles the lynxes in having similar tufts on the ears.<ref name=\"skinner\">{{cite book|last1=Skinner|first1=J.D.|last2=Chimimba|first2=C.T.|title=The Mammals of the Southern African Sub-region|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-1107-394-056|pages=397\u2013400|edition=3rd (revised)}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology and behaviour==\n\nThe Canada lynx tends to be [[nocturnality|nocturnal]] like its primary prey, the snowshoe hare. Nevertheless, activity may be observed during daytime.<ref name=Sunquist/> The lynx can cover {{convert|8|\u2013|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} every day to procure prey,<ref name=Saunders>{{cite journal|last1=Saunders|first1=J.K.|title=Movements and activities of the lynx in Newfoundland|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1963|volume=27|issue=3|pages=390\u2013400|jstor=3798512|doi=10.2307/3798512}}</ref><ref name=\"Nellis\">{{cite journal|last1=Nellis|first1=C.H.|last2=Keith|first2=L.B.|title=Hunting activities and success of lynxes in Alberta|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1968|volume=32|issue=4|pages=718\u2013722|jstor=3799545|doi=10.2307/3799545}}</ref> moving at {{convert|0.75|\u2013|1.46|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"ODonoghue\">{{cite journal|last1=O'Donoghue|first1=M.|last2=Boutin|first2=S.|last3=Krebs|first3=C.J.|last4=Zuleta|first4=G.|last5=Murray|first5=D.L.|last6=Hofer|first6=E.J.|title=Functional responses of coyotes and lynx to the snowshoe hare cycle|journal=Ecology|date=1998|volume=79|issue=4|pages=1193\u20131208|doi=10.1890/0012-9658(1998)079[1193:FROCAL]2.0.CO;2|url=https://www.math.unl.edu/~bdeng1/Teaching/math943/Topics/Data%20Fit/Odon98.pdf}}</ref> Lynxes are good swimmers;<ref name=Nowak/> one account records a lynx swimming {{convert|2|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} across the [[Yukon River]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Forest Cats of North America Cougars, Bobcats, Lynx |last= Kobalenko |first= J. |year= 1997 |publisher= Firefly Books |location= Ontario |isbn= 978-1-55209-172-2 |page=35 }}</ref> Canada lynxes are efficient climbers, and will dodge predators by climbing high up on trees, but they hunt only on the ground.<ref name=Hunter/> These lynxes are primarily solitary, with minimal social interaction except for the bond between mothers and female offspring, and the temporary association between individuals of opposite sexes during the mating season.<ref name=Parker/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carbyn|first1=L.|last2=Patriquin|first2=D.|title=Observations on home range sizes, movements, and social organization of lynx, (''Lynx canadensis''), in Riding Mountains National Park, Manitoba|journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist|pages=262\u2013267|volume=97|date=1983|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275651457}}</ref> Individuals of the same sex particularly tend to avoid each other, forming \"intrasexual\" territories\u2014a social structure similar to that found in bobcats, cougars, [[mustelid]]s and [[ursidae|ursids]]. Intraspecific aggression and consequent cannibalism (more common when food is scarce) are rare.<ref name=ruggiero>{{cite book |editor1-last=Ruggiero |editor1-first=L.F. |editor2-last=Aubry |editor2-first=K.B. |editor3-last=Buskirk |editor3-first=S.W. |editor4-last=Koehler |editor4-first=G.M. |editor5-last=Krebs |editor5-first=C.J. |editor6-last=McKelvey |editor6-first=K.S. |editor7-last=Squires |editor7-first=J.R. |title=Ecology and conservation of lynx in the United States (General Technical Report RMRS-GTR-30WWW) |date=1999 |chapter=Ecology of lynx in northern Canada and Alaska |pages=265\u2013306 |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture, Forest Service, Rocky Mountain Research Station |location=Fort Collins, Colorado, US |url=https://www.fs.fed.us/rm/pubs/rmrs_gtr030.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Fisher (animal)|Fisher]]s are known to occasionally hunt Canada lynxes in the northeastern United States; a study in northern [[Maine]] identified predation by fishers as the leading cause of Canada lynx mortality over 12 years, though it did not appear to affect population growth in the lynxes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McLellan |first1=S. R. |last2=Vashon |first2=J. H. |last3=Johnson |first3=E. L. |last4=Crowley |first4=S. M. |last5=Vashon |first5=A. D. |title=Fisher predation on Canada lynx in the Northeastern United States |journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management |date=2018 |volume=82 |issue=8 |pages=1775\u20131783 |doi=10.1002/jwmg.21538}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Learn|first=J.R.|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2018/09/Weasel-like-fishers-prey-on-Canada-Lynx-in-Maine-news/|title=Small weasel-like animals are taking down big cats|date=28 September 2018|website=[[National Geographic]]|publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]|accessdate = 16 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe Canada lynx is known to host several [[Parasitism|parasite]]s including ''[[Cylicospirura felineus]]'', ''[[Taenia (cestode)|Taenia]]'' species, ''[[Toxocara cati]]'', ''[[Toxascaris leonina]]'' and ''[[Troglostrongylus wilsoni]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=van Zyll de Jong |first1=C. G. |title=Parasites of the Canada lynx, ''Felis (Lynx) canadensis'' (Kerr) |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |date=1966 |volume=44 |issue=4 |pages=499\u2013509 |doi=10.1139/z66-054|pmid=5944283 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=J. D. |last2=Addison |first2=E. M. |last3=Joachim |first3=D. G. |last4=Smith |first4=L. M. |last5=Quinn |first5=N. W. S. |title=Helminth parasites of Canada lynx (''Felis canadensis'') from northern Ontario |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |date=1986 |volume=64 |issue=2 |pages=358\u2013364 |doi=10.1139/z86-057}}</ref> Canada lynxes could have played a role in the transmission of the [[zoonosis|zoonotic]] parasite ''[[Toxoplasma gondii]]'' to the [[Inuit]] in North America.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reiling |first1=S. J. |last2=Dixon |first2=B. R. |title=''Toxoplasma gondii'': How an Amazonian parasite became an Inuit health issue |journal= Canada Communicable Disease Report|date=2019 |volume=45 |issue=7/8 |pages=183\u2013190 |doi=10.14745/ccdr.v45i78a03 |pmid=31355827|pmc=6615440 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simon |first1=A. |last2=Poulin |first2=M. B. |last3=Rousseau |first3=A. N. |last4=Dubey |first4=J. P. |last5=Ogden |first5=N. H. |title=Spatiotemporal dynamics of Toxoplasma gondii infection in Canadian lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') in Western Quebec, Canada |journal=Journal of Wildlife Diseases |date=2013 |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=39\u201348 |doi=10.7589/2012-02-048|pmid=23307370 }}</ref> A study in 2019 identified a [[gammaherpesvirus]] species in the Canada lynx for the first time. The study discovered a novel [[percavirus]], named LcaGHV1, in [[spleen]] samples of Canada lynxes from Maine and Newfoundland.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hendrikse |first1=L. D. |last2=Kambli |first2=A. |last3=Kayko |first3=C. |last4=Canuti |first4=M. |last5=Rodrigues |first5=B. |last6=Stevens |first6=B. |last7=Vashon |first7=J. |last8=Lang |first8=A. S. |last9=Needle |first9=D. B. |last10=Troyer |first10=R. M. |title=Identification of a novel gammaherpesvirus in Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') |journal=Viruses |date=2019 |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=363 |doi=10.3390/v11040363|pmid=31010021 |pmc=6520957 }}</ref> \n\n=== Relationship with the snowshoe hare ===\n[[File:Milliers fourrures vendues en environ 90 ans odum 1953 en.jpg|right|upright=2|thumb|Numbers of [[snowshoe hare]]s (''Lepus americanus'', yellow, background) and Canada lynx (black line, foreground) furs sold to the [[Hudson's Bay Company]]]]\nA [[Generalist and specialist species|specialist predator]], the Canada lynx depends heavily on snowshoe hares for food.<ref name=Hunter/> Snowshoe hare populations in Alaska and central Canada undergo cyclic rises and falls\u2014at times the population densities can fall from as high as {{convert|2,300|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}} to as low as {{convert|12|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}. Consequently, a period of hare scarcity occurs every 8 to 11 years. An example of a prey-predator cycle, the cyclic variations in snowshoe hare populations significantly affect the numbers of their predators\u2014lynxes and [[coyote]]s\u2014in the region. When the hare populations plummet, lynxes tend to move to areas with more hares, and tend to not produce litters; as the numbers of the hare increase, so does the population of the lynx.<ref name=\"Brand1979\">{{cite journal|last1=Brand|first1=C.J.|last2=Keith|first2=L.B.|title=Lynx demography during a snowshoe hare decline in Alberta|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1979|volume=43|issue=4|pages=827\u2013849|doi=10.2307/3808267|jstor=3808267}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=M. |last2=Boutin |first2=S. |last3=Krebs |first3=C.J. |last4=Hofer |first4=E.J. |title=Numerical responses of coyotes and lynx to the snowshoe hare cycle |journal=Oikos |date=1997 |volume=80 |issue=1 |pages=150\u2013162 |doi=10.2307/3546526|jstor=3546526 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ward |first1=R.M.P. |last2=Krebs |first2=C.J. |title=Behavioural responses of lynx to declining snowshoe hare abundance |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |date=1985 |volume=63 |issue=12 |pages=2817\u20132824 |doi=10.1139/z85-421}}</ref> In northern Canada, the abundance of lynxes can be estimated from the records kept of the number caught each year for their fur; records have been kept by the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] and [[Government of Canada|Canadian government]] since the 1730s.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Weinstein |first=M.S. |year=1977|title=Hares, lynx, and trappers |journal= The American Naturalist|volume= 111|issue=980 |pages=806\u20138 |doi=10.1086/283212 |jstor=2460337}}</ref> These cycles have been cited as one of the few examples of the [[Lotka-Volterra equations|Lotka\u2013Volterra predator\u2013prey equations]], caused by the interplay of three major factors\u2014food, predation and social interaction.<ref name=\"krebs2001\">{{cite journal |last1=Krebs |first1=C.J. |last2=Boonstra |first2=R. |last3=Boutin |first3=S. |last4=Sinclair |first4=A.R.E. |title=What drives the 10-year cycle of snowshoe hares?: The ten-year cycle of snowshoe hares\u2014one of the most striking features of the boreal forest\u2014 is a product of the interaction between predation and food supplies, as large-scale experiments in the Yukon have demonstrated |journal=BioScience |date=2001 |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=25\u201335 |doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2001)051[0025:WDTYCO]2.0.CO;2|url=https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article-pdf/51/1/25/26890541/51-1-25.pdf}}</ref> A study involving statistical modelling of the interspecific relations of the snowshoe hare, the plant species it feeds on and its predators (including the Canada lynx) suggested that while the demographics of the lynx depend primarily on the hare, the hare's dynamics depend both on the plant species in its diet and predators, of which the Canada lynx is just one.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stenseth |first1=N.C. |last2=Falck |first2=W. |last3=Bj\u00f8rnstad |first3=O.N. |last4=Krebs |first4=C.J. |title=Population regulation in snowshoe hare and Canadian lynx: Asymmetric food web configurations between hare and lynx |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=1997 |volume=94 |issue=10 |pages=5147\u201352 |doi=10.1073/pnas.94.10.5147 |pmid=9144205 |pmc=24646 |bibcode=1997PNAS...94.5147C |url=https://www.pnas.org/content/pnas/94/10/5147.full.pdf}}</ref> Environmental factors such as forest fires, precipitation and snowfall might also significantly affect this prey-predator cycle.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fox |first1=J.F. |title=Forest fires and the snowshoe hare-Canada lynx cycle |journal=Oecologia |date=1978 |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=349\u2013374 |doi=10.1007/BF00346252}}</ref>\n\n===Home ranges===\n[[File:Canada lynx (6002291242).jpg|thumb|Lynxes are typically solitary with minimal social bonds.]]\nCanada lynxes establish [[home range]]s that vary widely in size, depending upon the method of measurement. The two common methods are examining the tracks of the lynx on snow (snow-tracking) and [[Wildlife radio telemetry|radio telemetry]]; snow-tracking generally gives smaller sizes for home ranges. Studies based on snow-tracking have estimated home range sizes of {{convert|11.1|\u2013|49.5|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, while those based on radio telemetry have given the area between {{convert|8|and|783|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=lox/> Like other cats, Canada lynxes [[Territorial marking|scent-mark]] their ranges by spraying urine and depositing faeces on snow or tree stumps and other prominent sites in and around their range.<ref name=Sunquist/>\n\nFactors such as availability of prey (primarily snowshoe hare), density of lynxes and the topography of the habitat determine the shape and size of the home range.<ref name=lox/> Studies have tried to correlate the abundance of snowshoe hares in an area with the sizes of lynx home ranges in that area. A 1985 study showed that the mean size of home ranges trebled\u2014from {{convert|13.2|to|39.2|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}\u2014when the density of hares fell from {{convert|14.7|to|1|/ha|/acre|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite journal|last1=Ward|first1=R.M.P.|last2=Krebs|first2=C.J.|title=Behavioural responses of lynx to declining snowshoe hare abundance|journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology|date=1985|volume=63|issue=12|pages=2817\u201324|doi=10.1139/z85-421}}</ref> However, a few other studies have reported different responses from lynxes at times of prey scarcity; some lynxes do not show any changes in their ranges, while others may resort to hunting in small areas, occupying small home ranges.<ref name=lox/> Canada lynxes generally do not leave their home ranges frequently, though limited prey availability can force lynxes to disperse or expand their ranges.<ref name=Poole1995>{{cite journal|last1=Poole|first1=K.G.|title=Spatial organization of a lynx population|journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology|date=1995|volume=73|issue=4|pages=632\u201341|doi=10.1139/z95-074}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Poole|first1=K.G.|title=Dispersal patterns of lynx in the Northwest Territories|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1997|volume=61|issue=2|pages=497\u2013505|doi=10.2307/3802607|jstor=3802607}}</ref>\n\nMales tend to occupy larger ranges than do females; for instance, data from a 1980 radio telemetric analysis in [[Minnesota]] showed that home ranges of males spread over {{convert|145|\u2013|243|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, while those of females covered {{convert|51|\u2013|122|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mech|first1=L.D.|title=Age, sex, reproduction, and spatial organization of lynxes colonizing Northeastern Minnesota|journal=Journal of Mammalogy|date=1980|volume=61|issue=2|pages=261\u20137|jstor=1380047|doi=10.2307/1380047}}</ref> In another radio telemetric study in 1985 in [[Montana]], male home ranges averaged {{convert|122|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} and those of females averaged {{convert|43.1|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Brainerd|first=S.M.|title=Reproductive ecology of bobcats and lynx in western Montana|type=M.Sc. thesis |publisher=[[University of Montana]]|date=1985|pages=1\u201385}}</ref> In a study in the southern [[Northwest Territories]], ranges of individuals of opposite sexes were found to overlap extensively, while the ranges of individuals of the same sex hardly coincided. The study suggested that individuals do not show any significant tendency to avoid or mingle with one another, and thus only passively defend their ranges.<ref name=Poole1995/> Female home ranges contract in size when the females have offspring to take care of, and expand to their original size at the time of weaning.<ref name=ruggiero/>\n\nA [[Genetics|genetic]] study showed that lynxes at the periphery of a population, given their smaller numbers and greater susceptibility to variations in the range, face more difficulty in breeding with lynxes toward the centre of the population and hence show lower [[genetic variability]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schwartz |first1=M.K. |last2=Mills |first2=L.S. |last3=Ortega |first3=Y. |last4=Ruggiero |first4=L.F. |last5=Allendorf |first5=F.W. |title=Landscape location affects genetic variation of Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') |journal=Molecular Ecology |date=2003 |volume=12 |issue=7 |pages=1807\u201316 |doi=10.1046/j.1365-294X.2003.01878.x|pmid=12803633 }}</ref>\n\n===Diet and hunting===\n[[File:Snowshoe Hare (6187109754).jpg|thumb|left|[[Snowshoe hare]], the primary prey of the Canada lynx]]\nThe Canada lynx preys primarily and almost exclusively on the snowshoe hare. These hares comprise 35\u201397% of their diet; the proportion varies by the season and the abundance of hares.<ref name=Hunter/> However, at times when the numbers of the hare drop, lynxes will include other animals in their diet\u2014such as ducks, [[grouse]], moles, [[ptarmigan]], [[red squirrel]]s, voles and young [[ungulate]]s ([[Dall's sheep]], [[mule deer]] and [[boreal woodland caribou|caribou]])\u2014though snowshoe hares continue to be the primary component. The Canada lynx tends to be less selective in summer and autumn, adding small mammals as a minor component of their diet besides the hare. The reason behind this is unclear\u2014it could be due to greater abundance of alternate prey, or reduced success in hunting hares.<ref name=ruggiero/> A study in Alaska found that lynxes played a role in the decrease in populations of [[red fox]], caribou and Dall's sheep when hares were very low in number.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stephenson |first1=R.O. |last2=Grangaard |first2=D.V. |last3=Burch |first3=J. |title=Lynx, ''Felis lynx'', predation on red foxes, ''Vulpes vulpes'', caribou, ''Rangifer tarandus'', and Dall sheep, ''Ovis dalli'', in Alaska |journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist |date=1991 |volume=105 |pages=255\u201362 |url=http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/static/home/library/pdfs/wildlife/propubs/91_stephenson_etal_lynx_predation_redfoxes_caribou_dallsheep_ak.pdf}}</ref> Canada lynxes ingest {{convert|0.6|\u2013|1.2|kg|lb}} of food everyday.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter/> Lynxes have also been reported feeding occasionally on [[Succulent plant|succulent]] [[sedge]]s and grasses.<ref name=yukongov/>\n\nCanadian lynxes hunt around twilight or at night, the time when snowshoe hares tend to be active.<ref name=Hunter/> Lynxes rely on their vision and sense of hearing to locate prey.<ref name=Nowak/> The lynx will roam or wait (in what researchers often term \"ambush beds\") on certain trails where snowshoe hares gather, pounce on a hare and kill it by a bite on its head, throat or the nape of its neck.<ref name=ruggiero/> Sometimes a chase of around ten bounds may be necessary to trap the prey. The lynx is assisted by its [[Stereopsis|stereoscopic vision]] in detecting prey and measuring distances. Staying in cover while hunting helps the lynx conserve energy in its frigid habitat by avoiding unnecessary movement.<ref name=yukongov/> Young ungulates are given a throat bite to suffocate them to death. The lynx may eat its kill immediately or cache it in snow or leaves to eat it over the next few days.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter/><ref name=ruggiero/> Studies suggest success in hunting hares depends heavily on the distance between the lynx and the hare when the lynx starts chasing it and their relative speeds, which in turn depends on the hunting prowess of the lynx, the alertness of the hare and the vegetation cover among other factors.<ref name=Sunquist/> Lynxes will occasionally hunt together, though studies differ on how this affects the hunting success rate compared to when an individual hunts alone.<ref name=ruggiero/> In fact, they may hunt in groups when hares are scarce.<ref name = dono98/> [[Scavenger|Scavenging]] is common in Canada lynxes; they will take ungulates killed by the cold or vehicles.<ref name=Hunter/>\n[[File:Lynx-canadensis.jpg|thumb|right|A lynx stalking its prey]]\nBoth coyotes and Canada lynxes are major predators of the snowshoe hare. A study showed that compared to lynxes, the feet of coyotes sink deeper in the snow due to their smaller size and hence a larger body mass to foot area ratio, prompting them to ambush their prey instead of chasing it like lynxes often do.<ref name=\"murray1991\">{{cite journal |last1=Murray |first1=D.L. |last2=Boutin |first2=S. |title=The influence of snow on lynx and coyote movements: does morphology affect behavior? |journal=Oecologia |date=1991 |volume=88 |issue=4 |pages=463\u20139 |doi=10.1007/BF00317707|pmid=28312614 |bibcode=1991Oecol..88..463M }}</ref> A study of the two species in southwest [[Yukon Territory]] showed that when the numbers of the hare increased, both predators killed more hares than were necessary for their subsistence; lynxes need to kill 0.4 to 0.5 hare per day to meet their energy requirements, but were observed to kill 1.2 hares per day during this period. Coyotes, with a success rate of 36.9%, emerged as more successful hunters than lynxes that succeeded in 28.7% of their hunts; however this may have resulted from the greater number of adult coyotes in the studied population. Lynxes rarely cached their kills, unlike coyotes, and this may have led to incomplete consumption of some kills. During the cyclic decrease in snowshoe hare numbers, both predators hunted for the same time period as they did when hares were abundant, but lynxes killed more hares than they did earlier. Moreover, lynxes supplemented their diet with red squirrels.<ref name=ODonoghue/><ref name=dono98>{{cite journal |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=M. |last2=Boutin |first2=S. |last3=Krebs |first3=C.J. |last4=Murray|first4=D.L. |last5=Hofer |first5=E.J.| title=Behavioural responses of coyote and lynx to the snowshoe hare cycle |journal=Oikos |date=1998 |volume=82 |issue=1 |pages=169\u201383 |doi=10.2307/3546927|jstor=3546927 }}</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Canada Lynx Mom and Kitten (15250932421).jpg|thumb|left|A juvenile with its mother]]\n\nThe mating season is roughly a month long, from March to early April. Urine marking and mating calls are part of [[Display (zoology)|display behaviour]], and increases the interaction between individuals of opposite sexes. Females can be [[Induced ovulation (animals)|induced ovulators]] when the availability of mates is low, or spontaneous ovulators when several mates are available. Females have only a single [[estrus cycle]]; estrus lasts for three to five days in captivity.<ref name=Sunquist /> Individuals have been observed making long wailing vocalizations, probably as mating calls.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Slough |first1=B.G. |last2=Mowat |first2=G. |title=Some observations on the natural history and behaviour of the Canada Lynx, ''Lynx canadensis'' |journal=Canadian Field Naturalist |date=1998 |volume=112 |issue=1 |pages=32-36 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Brian_Slough/publication/268872103_Some_observations_on_the_natural_history_and_behaviour_of_the_Canada_Lynx_Lynx_canadensis/links/547a2cbc0cf293e2da2b5e05.pdf}}</ref> Before birth, the female prepares a maternal den, usually in very thick brush, and typically inside thickets of shrubs, trees or woody debris.<ref name=Kaufman/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Slough |first=B. G. |year=1999 |title=Characteristics of Canada lynx, ''Lynx canadensis'', maternal dens and denning habitat |journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist |volume=113 |issue=4 |pages=605\u2013608}}</ref> The home range of the expecting female shrinks and her activity at the den site increases.<ref name=Sunquist/>\n\nAfter a gestational period of two to three months, a litter of one to eight kittens is born.<ref name=Sunquist /> Lynx reproductive cycles and litter sizes have been observed to vary with prey availability; litter size would typically contract in years of snowshoe hare decline (along with high infant mortality rates), and increase when hares were abundant.<ref name=\"breitenmoser\">{{cite journal |last1=Breitenmoser |first1=U. |last2=Slough |first2=B.G. |last3=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten |first3=C. |title=Predators of cyclic prey: is the Canada lynx a victim or profiteer of the snowshoe hare cycle? |journal=Oikos |date=1993 |volume=66 |issue=3 |pages=551\u2013554 |doi=10.2307/3544952|jstor=3544952 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Slough |first1=B.G. |last2=Mowat |first2=G. |title=Lynx population dynamics in an untrapped refugium |journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management |date=1996 |volume=60 |issue=4 |pages=946\u2013961 |doi=10.2307/3802397}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=M.|first1=Garth |last2=Slough |first2=B.G. |last3=Boutin |first3=S.|title=Lynx recruitment during a snowshoe hare population peak and decline in southwest Yukon |journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management |date=1996 |volume=60 |issue=2 |pages=441\u2013452 |doi=10.2307/3802247}}</ref> Kittens weigh from {{convert|175|to|235|g|oz|abbr=on}} at birth, and initially have grayish buff fur with black markings. They are blind for the first 14 days, and [[weaning|weaned]] at 12 weeks. Most births occur from May to July. Kittens leave the den after about five weeks, and begin hunting at between seven and nine months of age. They leave the mother at around ten months, as the next breeding season begins, but do not reach the full adult size until around two years old. Female offspring typically settle in home ranges close to their mothers and remain in contact with them for life, while male offspring move far from their mother's range. Females reach sexual maturity at ten months, although they often delay breeding for another year, whereas males reach maturity at two or three years. Canada lynxes have been reported to live for up to 16 years in wild, though most do not make it beyond 10 years; in captivity the lifespan may be as long as 27 years.<ref name=Sunquist /><ref name=Hunter/>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n[[File:Young Lynx spotted west of Drayton Valley Ab - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Canada lynxes prefer dense [[boreal forest]]s.]]\nThe Canada lynx occurs predominantly in dense [[Taiga|boreal forest]]s, and its range heavily coincides with that of the snowshoe hare. Canada lynxes generally avoid open areas despite good prey availability; they face difficulty surviving in heavily logged areas and agricultural land, though they can thrive well in deforested areas which have been left to regenerate for 15 years or more. In the past, the lynx occurred from the northern United States (in 24 States), possibly up to the [[Rocky Mountains]] in [[New Mexico]], to the [[tree line]] in the Arctic through coniferous forests in Alaska and Canada. The lynx continues to occur in most of Alaska and its erstwhile range in Canada. In the United States, the lynx occurs in the  [[Blue Mountains (Pacific Northwest)|Blue Mountains]], [[Cascade Range]] and southern Rocky Mountains, [[Great Lakes region]] and [[New England]]. The lynx has been successfully reintroduced in [[Colorado]], where it had become extinct in the 1970s. Canada lynxes have been recorded up to an elevation of {{convert|4310|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter/>\n\nA Canada lynx was shot near [[Newton Abbot]] in the United Kingdom in 1903 after it attacked two dogs. The animal remained unidentified at the time and was preserved by [[Bristol Museum and Art Gallery]], and was finally identified in a 2014 study. The researchers concluded that it had probably been captive for some time, perhaps as an [[exotic pet]] or part of a travelling menagerie, but may have survived for a substantial period after escaping. They considered it \"the earliest recorded example of an exotic cat on the loose in the UK\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Blake |first1=M. |last2=Naish |first2=D. |last3=Larson |first3=G. |last4=King |first4=C.L. |last5=Nowell |first5=G. |last6=Sakamoto |first6=M. |last7=Barnett |first7=R. |title=Multidisciplinary investigation of a \u2018British big cat\u2019: a lynx killed in southern England c. 1903 |journal=Historical Biology |date=2013 |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=441\u2013448 |doi=10.1080/08912963.2013.785541}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-22263874|title='Big cat' Canada lynx was on the loose in UK in 1903|last=Morelle|first=R.|date=24 April 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Postmedia News |title=That 'British big cat' called England's Loch Ness Monster? Its legend was fuelled by Canadian lynx, study says |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/that-british-big-cat-thats-like-englands-loch-ness-monster-its-legend-was-fuelled-by-a-canadian-lynx-study-says |accessdate=9 April 2020 |publisher=National Post |date=26 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mohan |first1=G. |title=British big cat theory gets bump from lynx link |url=https://www.latimes.com/science/la-xpm-2013-apr-24-la-sci-sn-big-cats-britain-20130424-story.html |accessdate=9 April 2020 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=24 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation ==\n[[File:Felis lynx canadensis (Canadian lynx) fur skin back.jpg|thumb|left|Canada lynxes are trapped for their fur.]]\nCanada lynxes are trapped in specific periods or seasons for fur trade in most of Alaska and Canada; hunting seasons and quotas are set based on population data. Even without regulations in place, the lynx-hare cycles and the distribution of the lynx have remained unaffected over the last century. In eastern Canada the lynx is threatened by competition with the [[eastern coyote]], whose numbers in the region have rose in the last few decades. Habitat loss is the main threat in the [[contiguous United States]], while trapping is a relatively insignificant cause of mortality. Hybridization between Canada lynxes and bobcats has been reported in the southern periphery of the range, and does not appear to be a threat to Canada lynxes.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Homyack, J.A. |year=2008|title=Canada Lynx-Bobcat (''Lynx canadensis \u00d7 L.rufus'') hybrids at the southern periphery of lynx range in Maine, Minnesota and New Brunswick|url=http://www.fs.fed.us/rm/pubs_other/rmrs_2008_homyack_j001.pdf|journal= American Midland Naturalist |volume=159|pages=504\u2013508|doi=10.1674/0003-0031(2008)159[504:CLLCLR]2.0.CO;2|issue=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Schwartz, M.K. | year = 2004 | title = Hybridization between Canada Lynx and bobcats: genetic results and management implications| journal = Conservation Genetics | volume = 5 | pages = 349\u2013355 | doi = 10.1023/B:COGE.0000031141.47148.8b | issue = 3|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/225195035_Hybridization_Between_Canada_Lynx_and_Bobcats_Genetic_Results_and_Management_Implications }}</ref>\n\nThe Canada lynx is abundant over its broad range, and is not significantly threatened by its legal use in the international fur trade since more than two centuries. Therefore, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]] (IUCN) classifies the Canada lynx as [[Least Concern]]. However, populations are relatively lower in the southern half of the range and are protected from killing for fur trade. The lynx is listed as Endangered in [[New Brunswick]] and [[Nova Scotia]].<ref name=iucn/> On March 24, 2000, the [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]] (USFWS) issued its Final Rule, which designated the Canada lynx a Threatened Species in 14 contiguous United States.<ref name=\"FedReg\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-2000-03-24/pdf/00-7145.pdf|title=Endangered and Threatened Wildlife and Plants; Determination of Threatened Status for the Contiguous U.S. Distinct Population Segment of the Canada Lynx and Related Rule |page=16051\u201316086|journal=Federal Register|volume= 65|issue= 58 |date= 24 March 2000|publisher=Department of the Interior, Fish and Wildlife Service}}</ref> In 2005, the USFWS demarcated six major areas for revival where lynx populations had been reported in the past two decades: northern Maine and [[New Hampshire]], northeastern Minnesota, northwestern Montana and northeastern [[Idaho]], the [[Kettle River Range]] and the \"Wedge area\" between the [[Kettle River (Columbia River tributary)|Kettle]] and [[Columbia River|Columbia]] rivers of [[Washington (state)|Washington]], the northern Cascade Range of Washington, and the [[Greater Yellowstone]] area of [[Wyoming]], Montana and Idaho.<ref name=iucn/> By 2010, after an 11-year effort, the lynx had been successfully reintroduced into Colorado. The initial introduction was in the [[San Juan Mountains]] in southwestern Colorado, but self-sustaining populations were established throughout the south-central Colorado Rockies as far north as [[Summit County, Colorado|Summit County]].<ref>{{cite report|title=Success of the Colorado Division of Wildlife\u2019s lynx reintroduction program|url=http://wildlife.state.co.us/NR/rdonlyres/6EBDE944-FF9A-4CE4-894D-8547184CB8BA/0/ColoradoLynxReintroductionAssessment_090710.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718225119/http://wildlife.state.co.us/NR/rdonlyres/6EBDE944-FF9A-4CE4-894D-8547184CB8BA/0/ColoradoLynxReintroductionAssessment_090710.pdf|date=18 July 2011|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=dead|pages=1\u20134|publisher=Colorado Parks and Wildlife}}</ref> A 2012 study showed that numbers have improved in the northeastern United States;<ref>{{cite report|last1=Vashon |first1=J. |last2=McLellan |first2=S. |last3=Crowley |first3=S. |last4=Meehan |first4=A. |last5=Laustsen |first5=K. |title=Canada Lynx Assessment |date=2012 |pages=1\u2013107 |url=https://www.maine.gov/ifw/docs/species_planning/mammals/canadalynx/Lynx%20Assessment%202012_Final.pdf |publisher=Maine Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife Research and Assessment Section |location=Maine}}</ref> however a 2008 study showed lynx populations were not doing well in Washington due to [[habitat fragmentation]]. A 2017 study reported increasing numbers in many areas in the United States.<ref>{{cite report|author1=[[US Fish and Wildlife Service]] |title=Species Status Assessment for the Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') Contiguous United States Distinct Population Segment. Version 1.0 |date=2017 |pages=1-300 |url=https://www.fws.gov/mountain-prairie/es/species/mammals/lynx/SSA2018/01112018_SSA_Report_CanadaLynx.pdf |publisher=Contiguous United States Distinct Population Segment |location=Colorado}}</ref> In January 2018, the USFWS declared that the Canada lynx no longer needed special protections in the United States following measures to preserve their populations, and their \"Threatened\" status may be revoked in the future.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/US-says-snow-loving-lynx-no-longer-need-special-protection-468986383.html|title=US says snow-loving lynx no longer need special protection|date=12 January 2018|author=Associated Press|publisher=KTUU-TV|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Mammals}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|Lynx canadensis}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lynx canadensis}}\n* [http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=97 Species portrait Canada lynx; IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group]\n* [http://ecos.fws.gov/speciesProfile/SpeciesReport.do?spcode=A073 U.S. Fish & Wildlife \"Species Profile\" and lynx article index]\n* [http://www.nrri.umn.edu/lynx/ Canada lynx research] at the [[University of Minnesota Duluth|University of Minnesota \u2013 Duluth]]\n* [https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/359/2/krebs.2001%20bioscience.pdf What Drives the 10-year Cycle of Snowshoe Hares?]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100714115216/http://www.voiceforthewild.org/mbnf/pubs/rdls/rdls.html Medicine Bow National Forest (A Habitat of the Canada Lynx)]\u2014Biodiversity Conservation Alliance\n* [http://www.rmrs.nau.edu/wildlife/forest_carnivores/lynx/ Forest Service Canada lynx research]\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q146457}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lynx, Canada}}\n[[Category:Arctic land animals]]\n[[Category:Ecological experiments]]\n[[Category:ESA threatened species]]\n[[Category:Fauna of New England]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Great Lakes region (North America)]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Plains-Midwest (United States)]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Rocky Mountains]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Western United States]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Lynx]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1792]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Canada]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Small wild cat}}\n{{Redirect|Canadian lynx|other species of lynx|Lynx}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Canada lynx\n| image = Canada_lynx_by_Michael_Zahra.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |publisher=[[IUCN]] |author=Vashon, J. |date=2016 |title=''Lynx canadensis'' |page=e.T12518A101138963 |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/12518/101138963 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-2.RLTS.T12518A101138963.en}}</ref>\n| genus = Lynx\n| species = canadensis\n| authority = [[Robert Kerr (writer)|Kerr]], 1792\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision = \n{{collapsible list|\n''L. c. canadensis'' (mainland lynx) <small>Kerr, 1792</small><br>\n''L. c. subsolanus'' (Newfoundland lynx) <small>[[Outram Bangs|Bangs]], 1897</small><br>\n''L. c. mollipilosus'' (Arctic lynx) <small>[[Witmer Stone|Stone]], 1900</small>\n}}\n| range_map =CanadaLynx distribution2016.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution of Canada lynx (2016)<ref name=iucn/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Canada lynx''' (''Lynx canadensis'') is a medium-sized [[lynx]] native to [[North America]]. It ranges across [[Canada]] and [[Alaska]] extending into the United States portion of the [[Rocky Mountains]]. It is characterized by its long, dense fur, triangular ears with black tufts at the tips, and broad, [[snowshoe]]-like paws. Similar to the [[bobcat]] (''L. rufus''), the hindlimbs are remarkably longer than the forelimbs, so that the back appears to be sloping downward to the front. The lynx is a good swimmer and an agile climber. The Canada lynx stands {{convert|48|\u2013|56|cm|in|abbr=on}} tall at the shoulder and weighs between {{convert|5|and|17|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. This lynx was first [[scientific description|described]] by [[Robert Kerr (writer)|Robert Kerr]] in 1792. Three [[subspecies]] are recognized.\n\nThe Canada lynx is typically [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]] like its primary prey, the [[snowshoe hare]]. The strong dependence of this [[Specialist and generalist species|specialist predator]] on snowshoe hares for food leads to an example of a prey-predator cycle. Canada lynxes respond to the cyclic rises and falls over the years in snowshoe hare populations in Alaska and central Canada\u2014when hares are scarce lynxes tend to move to areas with more hares and tend to not produce litters, and as the numbers of the hare increase, so does the population of the lynx. The lynx waits for the hare in specific trails or \"ambush beds\", then pounces on it and kills it by a bite on its head, throat or the nape of its neck. Individuals of the same sex particularly tend to avoid each other, forming \"intrasexual\" territories. The mating season is roughly a month long (from March to early April). After a gestational period of two to three months, a litter of one to eight kittens is born. Offspring are weaned at 12 weeks.\n\nThis lynx occurs predominantly in dense [[Taiga|boreal forest]]s, and its range heavily coincides with that of the snowshoe hare. Given its abundance throughout its range and no severe threats, this lynx has been listed as [[Least Concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]]. This lynx is regularly trapped for the international fur trade in most of Alaska and Canada, but is protected in the southern half of its range due to threats such as habitat loss.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nIn his 1792 work ''The Animal Kingdom'', Scottish scientific writer [[Robert Kerr (writer)|Robert Kerr]] [[Scientific description|described]] a [[Lynx (genus)|lynx]] from Canada, giving it the [[Binomial nomenclature|name]] ''Felis lynx canadensis''.<ref name=\"Kerr1792\">{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=R. |authorlink=Robert Kerr (writer) |title=The Animal Kingdom |date=1792 |publisher=A. Strahan & T. Cadell |location=London |pages=157\u2212158 |chapterurl=https://archive.org/details/animalkingdomorz00linn/page/157 |chapter=''F. Lynx canadensis''}}</ref> The [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomy]] of the Canada lynx remained disputed through the 20th and early 21st centuries. In 1912, American zoologist [[Gerrit Miller]] placed the Canada lynx under the [[Genus (biology)|genus]] ''Lynx'', with the name ''L. canadensis''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Miller |first1=G. S. Jr. |authorlink = Gerrit Miller  |title=List of North American land mammals in the United States National Museum, 1911 |publisher=United States National Museum |pages=118\u2212121 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bulletinunitedst791912unit#page/118/mode/2up |location = Washington, D.C. |date = 1912}}</ref> Until as late as the early 2000s, scientists were divided on whether ''Lynx'' should be considered a [[Subgenus (biology)|subgenus]] of ''Felis'', or a [[Subfamily (biology)|subfamily]] itself; some even doubted if the Canada lynx should be considered a species on its own.<ref name=Tumlison>{{cite journal |last1=Tumlison |first1=R. |title=''Felis lynx''|journal=[[Mammalian Species]] |date=1987 |issue=269 |pages=1\u20138 |doi=10.2307/3503985 |jstor=3503985}}</ref><ref name=\"lox\">{{cite book |chapter=Lynx |last1=Koehler|first1=G. M.|last2=Aubry|first2=K. B. |title=The Scientific Basis for Conserving Forest Carnivores: American Marten, Fisher, Lynx and Wolverine in the Western United States |date=1994 |publisher=Diane Publishing |location=Colorado |editor1-last=Zielinski |editor1-first=W. J.|editor2-last=Kucerala|editor2-first=T. E. |isbn=978-0-7881-3628-3 |pages=74\u201398 |chapterurl={{Google Books|id=U88sJR0GWtMC|page=74|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=\"Anderson\">{{cite book |last1=Anderson|first1=E. M. |last2=Lovallo |first2=M. J. |chapter=Bobcat and lynx |pages=758\u2013786 |editor1-last=Feldhamer|editor1-first=G. A.|editor2-last=Thompson|editor2-first=B. C.|editor3-last=Chapman |editor3-first=J. A. |title=Wild Mammals of North America: Biology, Management, and Conservation |date=2003 |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=978-0-8018-7416-1 |edition=2nd|chapterurl={{Google Books|id=-xQalfqP7BcC|page=758|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> American zoologist [[W. Chris Wozencraft|W. C. Wozencraft]] revised the classification of [[Carnivora]] in 2005, and recognized the Canada lynx as a species under ''Lynx'', along with the [[bobcat]] (''L. rufus''), the [[Eurasian lynx]] (''L. lynx'') and the [[Iberian lynx]] (''L. pardinus''). In 2017, the Cat Classification Task Force of the [[IUCN]] Cat Specialist Group revised felid taxonomy, considering the Canada lynx a [[monotypic species]].<ref name=\"Catsg2017\">{{cite journal |author1=Kitchener, A. C. |author2=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten, C. |author3=Eizirik, E. |author4=Gentry, A. |author5=Werdelin, L. |author6=Wilting, A. |author7=Yamaguchi, N. |author8=Abramov, A. V. |author9=Christiansen, P. |author10=Driscoll, C. |author11=Duckworth, J. W. |author12=Johnson, W. |author13=Luo, S.-J. |author14=Meijaard, E. |author15=O'Donoghue, P. |author16=Sanderson, J. |author17=Seymour, K. |author18=Bruford, M. |author19=Groves, C. |author20=Hoffmann, M. |author21=Nowell, K. |author22=Timmons, Z. |author23=Tobe, S. |year=2017 |title=A revised taxonomy of the Felidae: The final report of the Cat Classification Task Force of the IUCN Cat Specialist Group |journal=Cat News |issue=Special Issue 11 |pages=41\u221242 |url=https://repository.si.edu/bitstream/handle/10088/32616/A_revised_Felidae_Taxonomy_CatNews.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y}}</ref><!--this is not about taxonomy: <ref name=CanLynx>{{cite report |last1=Meaney |first1=C. |last2=Beauvais |first2=G. P. |title=Species assessment for Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') in Wyoming |publisher= [[United States Department of the Interior]], Bureau of Land Management |location=}}</ref> -->\n\nWozencraft recognized three [[subspecies]] of the Canada lynx in ''[[Mammal Species of the World]]'' (2005):<ref name = Catsg2017/><ref name = msw3>{{MSW3 Wozencraft |pages=541 |id=14000152 |heading=Species ''Lynx canadensis''}}</ref>\n\n* ''L. c. canadensis'' (mainland lynx) <small>Kerr, 1792</small>: Occurs in the Canadian mainland.\n* ''L. c. mollipilosus'' (Arctic lynx) <small>[[Witmer Stone|Stone]], 1900</small>: Described from the skin and skull of a male lynx killed near [[Wainwright, Alaska|Wainwright]], [[Alaska]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stone |first1=W. |authorlink=Witmer Stone |year=1900 |title=Report on the birds and mammals collected by the McIlhenny Expedition to Pt. Barrow, Alaska |journal=Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia |volume=52 |pages=4\u221249 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofaca52acaduoft/page/48}}</ref>\n* ''L. c. subsolanus'' (Newfoundland lynx) <small>[[Outram Bangs|Bangs]], 1897</small>: Described from a lynx skin and skull collected near [[Codroy]], [[Newfoundland]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bangs |first1=O. |authorlink=Outram Bangs|year=1897 |title=Notes on the lynxes of eastern North America, with descriptions of two new species |journal=Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington |volume=11 |pages=47\u221251 |url=https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofbio11biol/page/46}}</ref>\n\nA study of the differences (in factors such as coat colour, cranial measurements and weights) between the mainland and Newfoundland forms showed that apart from a few variations (for instance, the Newfoundland lynx features a darker coat than the mainland subspecies), the standard measurements are not significantly distinct. Noting only a few differences between the two forms, the study suggested the Newfoundland lynx to have [[genetic divergence|diverged]] only recently from the mainland form. The lack of appreciable subspecific distinctions led the researchers to doubt the vaidity of the Newfoundland lynx as a separate subspecies.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Van Zyll de Jong |first1=C. G. |date=1975 |title=Differentiation of the Canada lynx, ''Felis'' (''Lynx'') ''canadensis subsolana'', in Newfoundland |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |volume=53 |issue=50 |pages=699\u2212705 |doi=10.1139/z75-085}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rueness |first1= E. K. |last2=Stenseth |first2=N. C. |last3=O\u2019Donoghue |first3=M. |last4=Boutin |first4=S. |last5=Ellegren |first5=H. |last6=& Jakobsen |first6=K. S. |date=2003 |title=Ecological and genetic spatial structuring in the Canada lynx |journal=Nature |volume=425 |issue= 6953 |pages=69\u221272|doi=10.1038/nature01942|pmid= 12955141 |bibcode= 2003Natur.425...69R }}</ref> A study in 2019 estimated the Newfoundland lynx to have diverged from the mainland lynx around 20,000 to 33,000 years ago following the [[Last Glacial Period|last glaciation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mer\u00f6ndun |first1=J. |last2=Murray |first2=D. L. |last3=Shafer |first3=A. B. A. |title=Genome\u2010scale sampling suggests cryptic epigenetic structuring and insular divergence in Canada lynx |journal=Molecular Ecology |volume=28 |issue=13 |pages=3186\u20133196 |date=2019 |doi=10.1111/mec.15131|pmid=31087722 }}</ref>\n\n== Evolution ==\n[[File:Lynx issiodorensis 2.JPG|thumb|right|Fossils of the [[Issoire lynx]] (''L. issiodorensis''), which is believed to be the ancestor of the four modern ''Lynx'' species]]\nAccording to a 2006 [[phylogenetic]] study, the ancestor of five felid lineages \u2013 ''Lynx'', ''Leopardus'', ''Puma'', ''Felis'' and ''[[Prionailurus]]'' plus ''[[Otocolobus]]'' \u2013 arrived in North America after crossing the [[Bering Strait]] 8.5\u20138 [[Mya (unit)|mya]]. ''Lynx'' diverged from the ''Puma'', ''Felis'' and ''Prionailurus'' plus ''Otocolobus'' lineages around 3.24 mya.<ref name=Johnson2006/> The [[Issoire lynx]] (''L. issiodorensis''), that probably originated in Africa 4 mya and occurred in Europe and northern Asia until it fell to extinction around 1 mya, is believed to be the ancestor of the four modern species of ''Lynx''.<ref name=\"Sunquist\">{{cite book|last1=Sunquist|first1=M.|last2=Sunquist|first2=F.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2002|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago|isbn=978-0-226-77999-7|pages=152\u201363|chapter=Canada lynx|chapterurl={{Google Books|id=hFbJWMh9-OAC|pages=152\u2212163 |plainurl=yes}} }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kurt\u00e9n|first1=B.|title=The lynx from Etouaires, ''Lynx issiodorensis'' (Croizet & Jobert), Late Pliocene|journal=Annales Zoologici Fennici|date=1978|volume=15|issue=4|pages=314\u2013322|jstor=23733663|url=http://www.sekj.org/PDF/anzf15/anzf15-314-322.pdf}}</ref> A 1987 study suggested that the populations of the Eurasian lynx that reached North America 20,000 years ago initially settled in the southern half of the continent, as the northern part was covered by glaciers. The southern populations gradually evolved into the modern bobcat. Later, when the continent was invaded by the Eurasian lynx for a second time, the populations that settled in the northern part of the continent, now devoid of glaciers, evolved into the Canada lynx.<ref name=\"Quinn1987\">{{cite book |last1=Quinn|first1=N.W.S.|last2=Parker|first2=G.|editor1-last=Novak|editor1-first=M.|editor2-last=Baker|editor2-first=J.|editor3-last=Obbard|editor3-first=M.|title= Furbearer Management and Conservation in North America|chapter=Lynx|pages=683\u2013694|date=1987|publisher=Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources|location=Ontario|isbn=978-0-7743-9365-2}}</ref> The 2006 study gave the phylogenetic relationships of the Canada lynx as follows:<ref name=Johnson2006>{{cite journal | author = Johnson, W.E. | author2 = Eizirik, E. | author3 = Pecon-Slattery, J. | author4 = Murphy, W.J. | author5 = Antunes, A. | author6 = Teeling, E. | author7 = O'Brien, S.J. | last-author-amp = yes | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1126/science.1122277 | title = The Late Miocene radiation of modern Felidae: A genetic assessment | journal = [[Science (journal)|Science]] | volume = 311 | pages = 73\u201377 | pmid = 16400146 | issue = 5757| bibcode = 2006Sci...311...73J | url = https://zenodo.org/record/1230866 }}</ref><ref name=\"werdelin\">{{cite book |last1=Werdelin |first1=L. |author1-link = Lars Werdelin|last2=Yamaguchi |first2=N. |last3=Johnson |first3=W. E. |last4=O'Brien |first4=S. J. |chapter=Phylogeny and evolution of cats (Felidae)|date=2010|pages=59\u201382 |chapterurl=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/266755142|editor1-last=Macdonald|editor1-first=D.W.|editor2-last=Loveridge|editor2-first=A.J.|title=Biology and Conservation of Wild Felids|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-923445-5|edition=Reprint}}</ref>\n{{clade|style=font-size:90%;line-height:75%;\n|1={{clade\n   |1=''[[Leopardus]]''\n   |2={{clade\n      |label1=''[[Lynx]]''\n      |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Bobcat]] (''L. rufus'')\n         |2={{clade\n            |1='''Canada lynx''' (''L. canadensis'')\n            |2={{clade\n               |1=[[Iberian lynx]] (''L. pardinus'')\n               |2=[[Eurasian lynx]] (''L. lynx'')\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      |2={{clade\n         |label1=''[[Puma (genus)|Puma]]''\n         |1={{clade\n         |1=[[Cheetah]] (''Acinonyx jubatus'')\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=[[Cougar]] (''Puma concolor'')\n            |2=[[Jaguarundi]] (''P. yagouaroundi'')\n            }}\n            }}\n         |2={{clade\n            |1=''[[Felis]]''  \n            |2={{clade\n               |1=[[Pallas's cat]] (''Otocolobus manul'')\n               |2=''[[Prionailurus]]''\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n     }}\n}}\n}}\n\n== Physical characteristics ==\n[[File:Lynx (5300913523).jpg|thumb|A close facial view of the Canada lynx. The black ear tufts are characteristic of lynxes.]]\n\nThe Canada lynx is a lean, medium-sized cat characterized by its long, dense fur, triangular ears with black tufts at the tips, and broad, [[snowshoe]]-like paws. Similar to the bobcat, the hindlimbs are remarkably longer than the forelimbs, so that the back appears to be sloping downward to the front. The Canada lynx is [[sexually dimorphic]], with males larger and heavier than females. The lynx is between {{convert|73|and|107|cm|in|abbr=on}} in head-and-body length and stands {{convert|48|\u2013|56|cm|in|abbr=on}} tall at the shoulder; females weigh around {{convert|5|\u2013|12|kg|lb|abbr=on}} while males weigh around {{convert|6|\u2013|17|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Sunquist/> Physical proportions do not vary significantly across the range and are probably [[natural selection|naturally selected]] to allow survival on smaller prey.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Werdelin|first1=L.|authorlink=Lars Werdelin|title=The evolution of lynxes|journal=Annales Zoologici Fennici|url=http://lynx.uio.no/lynx/ibelynxco/04_library/4_3_publications/W/Werdelin_1981_Evolution_of_lynxes.pdf|date=1981|volume=18|issue=1|pages=37\u201371|jstor=23734102|access-date=June 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005114343/http://lynx.uio.no/lynx/ibelynxco/04_library/4_3_publications/W/Werdelin_1981_Evolution_of_lynxes.pdf|archive-date=October 5, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Eurasian lynx, that prefers prey the size of a [[roe deer]], is twice the size of the Canada lynx, that feeds primarily on the [[snowshoe hare]].<ref name=Sunquist/> The stubby tail, typical of lynxes, is {{convert|5|\u2013|13|cm|in|abbr=on}} long; while the bobcat's tail is black only in the upper part, the tail of the Canada lynx has a completely black tip.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter>{{cite book|last1=Hunter|first1=L.|title=Wild Cats of the World|date=2015|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|location=London|isbn=978-1-4729-2285-4|pages=146\u2013151|url={{Google Books|id=hzNBCgAAQBAJ|page=146|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> \n\nThe long, dense fur, uniformly coloured with little to no markings except on the underside, insulates the lynx in its frosty habitat. The fur is typically yellowish brown, though in Newfoundland it can vary from brown or buff-gray in spring and summer to a grayish shade with a grizzled appearance in winter; the underparts are white and may have a few dark spots.<ref name=\"Nowak\">{{cite book|last1=Nowak|first1=R.M.|title=Walker's Mammals of the World|date=1999|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8|pages=807\u2013808|edition=6th|url={{Google Books|id=T37sFCl43E8C|page=806|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref><ref name=Sunquist/> Although no [[Melanism|melanistic]] or [[Albinism (biology)|albinistic]] forms of the Canada lynx are known, \"blue\" lynxes have been reported in Alaska.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schwarz|first1=E.|title=Blue or dilute mutation in Alaskan lynx|journal=Journal of Mammalogy|date=1938|volume=19|issue=3|page=376|doi=10.1093/jmammal/19.3.376-a}}</ref> The fur is generally shorter in summer than in winter.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reid|first1=F.A.|title=Peterson Field Guide to Mammals of North America|date=2006|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Co.|location=Boston, US|isbn=978-0-547-34553-6|pages=94; 436\u2013437|edition=4th|url={{Google Books|id=jdw0oSIez34C|pg=PA46-IA1|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The backs of the ears are brown with a silvery-gray spot at the centre.<ref name=Tumlison/> Similar to other lynxes, black tufts around {{convert|4|cm|in}} in length emerge from the tips of the ears, which are lined with black fur.<ref name=Hunter/> In winter, the hair on the lower cheek becomes longer, giving the impression of a ruffle covering the throat. There are four nipples.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Nowak/> \n[[File:Canadian lynx by Keith Williams.jpg|thumb|left|As the forelimbs of the Canada lynx are shorter than the hindlimbs, the back appears to be sloping downward toward the front. Note the stubby tail and the dense fur.]]\nThe large, broad paws are covered in long, thick fur and can spread as wide as {{convert|10|cm|in}} to move fast and easily on soft snow.<ref name=Anderson/> The paws of a Canada lynx can support nearly double the weight those of a bobcat can bear before sinking.<ref name=lox/><ref name=Parker>{{cite journal|last1=Parker|first1=G.R.|last2=Maxwell|first2=J.W.|last3=Morton|first3=L.D.|last4=Smith|first4=G.E.J.|title=The ecology of the lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') on Cape Breton Island|journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology|date=1983|volume=61|issue=4|pages=770\u201386|doi=10.1139/z83-102}}</ref> Both species walk with the back foot typically following the front foot, and often do not follow a straight line path. The stride is {{convert|12|\u2013|18|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} for the lynx, while that of the bobcat varies between {{convert|5|and|16|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}}. Canada lynx tracks are generally larger than those of the bobcat; the thicker fur may make the toe pads appear less prominent in the snow. In dirt the tracks of the lynx are {{convert|3|\u2013|3.75|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} long and {{convert|3.5|\u2013|4.5|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} wide, whereas in snow they are bigger ({{convert|4.5|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} long and {{convert|5|in|cm|abbr=on|order=flip}} wide).<ref name = golden/><ref name=\"yukongov\">{{cite report|title=Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') |url=http://www.env.gov.yk.ca/animals-habitat/mammals/documents/Canada_Lynx.pdf |author=Environment Yukon |publisher=Government of Yukon}}</ref> The warm coat, wide paws and long legs serve as adaptations for the lynx to efficiently navigate and hunt in snow.<ref name=lox/>\n[[File:Brooks Range (19) Lynx trail.jpg|thumb|right|Canada lynx tracks in Alaska, with traces of fur]]\nThe Canada lynx has 28 teeth,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burt|first1=W.H.|title=A Field Guide to the Mammals: North America North of Mexico|date=1976|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Co.|location=Boston, US|isbn=978-0-395-91098-6|page=80|edition=3rd|url={{Google Books|id=O3l0WGH4CF4C|page=80|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> same as in other lynxes but unlike other felids that have 30,<ref name=Anderson/> with four long [[canine tooth|canines]] for puncturing and gripping. The lynx can feel where it is biting the prey with its canines because they are heavily laced with nerves. It also has four [[carnassial teeth]] that cut the meat into small pieces. In order for the lynx to use its carnassials, it must chew the meat with its head to its side. There are large spaces between the four canines and the rest of the teeth, and the second upper [[premolar]]s are absent, to ensure that the bite goes as deeply as possible into the prey.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Macdonald|first1=D.|title=The Velvet Claw: A Natural History of the Carnivores|date=1993|publisher=BBC Books|location=New York, US|isbn=978-0-563-20844-0|pages=47\u201350|url=https://archive.org/details/velvetclawnatura00macd|url-access=registration}}</ref> The claws are sharp and fully retractable (capable of being drawn within).<ref name=Tumlison/>\n\nThe Canada lynx can be told apart from the bobcat by its longer ear tufts, broader paws, shorter tail with a fully black tip, longer legs and the fewer markings and grayer shade of the coat.<ref name=Anderson/><ref name=golden>{{cite web|last1=Golden|first1=H.|last2=Krause|first2=T.|title=How to avoid incidental take of lynx while trapping or hunting bobcats and other furbearers|url=http://dnr.wi.gov/topic/trap/documents/avoidlinx.pdf|publisher=United States Fish & Wildlife Service and International Association of Fish and Wildlife Agencies|accessdate=19 July 2014|date=2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Kaufman\">{{cite book|last1=Bowers|first1=N.|last2=Bowers|first2=R.|last3=Kaufman|first3=K.|title=Kaufman Field Guide to Mammals of North America|date=2007|publisher=Houghton Mifflin|location=New York, US|isbn=978-0-618-95188-8|page=138|url={{Google Books|id=vfRgcZIOizEC|page=138|plainurl=yes}}}}</ref> The bobcat is generally smaller than the Canada lynx, but in areas where they are [[Sympatry|sympatric]] the bobcat tends to be larger and may still be confused with the Canada lynx.<ref name=Hunter/> The [[caracal]] resembles the lynxes in having similar tufts on the ears.<ref name=\"skinner\">{{cite book|last1=Skinner|first1=J.D.|last2=Chimimba|first2=C.T.|title=The Mammals of the Southern African Sub-region|date=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-1107-394-056|pages=397\u2013400|edition=3rd (revised)}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology and behaviour==\n\nThe Canada lynx tends to be [[nocturnality|nocturnal]] like its primary prey, the snowshoe hare. Nevertheless, activity may be observed during daytime.<ref name=Sunquist/> The lynx can cover {{convert|8|\u2013|9|km|mi|abbr=on}} every day to procure prey,<ref name=Saunders>{{cite journal|last1=Saunders|first1=J.K.|title=Movements and activities of the lynx in Newfoundland|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1963|volume=27|issue=3|pages=390\u2013400|jstor=3798512|doi=10.2307/3798512}}</ref><ref name=\"Nellis\">{{cite journal|last1=Nellis|first1=C.H.|last2=Keith|first2=L.B.|title=Hunting activities and success of lynxes in Alberta|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1968|volume=32|issue=4|pages=718\u2013722|jstor=3799545|doi=10.2307/3799545}}</ref> moving at {{convert|0.75|\u2013|1.46|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"ODonoghue\">{{cite journal|last1=O'Donoghue|first1=M.|last2=Boutin|first2=S.|last3=Krebs|first3=C.J.|last4=Zuleta|first4=G.|last5=Murray|first5=D.L.|last6=Hofer|first6=E.J.|title=Functional responses of coyotes and lynx to the snowshoe hare cycle|journal=Ecology|date=1998|volume=79|issue=4|pages=1193\u20131208|doi=10.1890/0012-9658(1998)079[1193:FROCAL]2.0.CO;2|url=https://www.math.unl.edu/~bdeng1/Teaching/math943/Topics/Data%20Fit/Odon98.pdf}}</ref> Lynxes are good swimmers;<ref name=Nowak/> one account records a lynx swimming {{convert|2|mi|km|order=flip|abbr=on}} across the [[Yukon River]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Forest Cats of North America Cougars, Bobcats, Lynx |last= Kobalenko |first= J. |year= 1997 |publisher= Firefly Books |location= Ontario |isbn= 978-1-55209-172-2 |page=35 }}</ref> Canada lynxes are efficient climbers, and will dodge predators by climbing high up on trees, but they hunt only on the ground.<ref name=Hunter/> These lynxes are primarily solitary, with minimal social interaction except for the bond between mothers and female offspring, and the temporary association between individuals of opposite sexes during the mating season.<ref name=Parker/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carbyn|first1=L.|last2=Patriquin|first2=D.|title=Observations on home range sizes, movements, and social organization of lynx, (''Lynx canadensis''), in Riding Mountains National Park, Manitoba|journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist|pages=262\u2013267|volume=97|date=1983|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/275651457}}</ref> Individuals of the same sex particularly tend to avoid each other, forming \"intrasexual\" territories\u2014a social structure similar to that found in bobcats, cougars, [[mustelid]]s and [[ursidae|ursids]]. Intraspecific aggression and consequent cannibalism (more common when food is scarce) are rare.<ref name=ruggiero>{{cite book |editor1-last=Ruggiero |editor1-first=L.F. |editor2-last=Aubry |editor2-first=K.B. |editor3-last=Buskirk |editor3-first=S.W. |editor4-last=Koehler |editor4-first=G.M. |editor5-last=Krebs |editor5-first=C.J. |editor6-last=McKelvey |editor6-first=K.S. |editor7-last=Squires |editor7-first=J.R. |title=Ecology and conservation of lynx in the United States (General Technical Report RMRS-GTR-30WWW) |date=1999 |chapter=Ecology of lynx in northern Canada and Alaska |pages=265\u2013306 |publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture, Forest Service, Rocky Mountain Research Station |location=Fort Collins, Colorado, US |url=https://www.fs.fed.us/rm/pubs/rmrs_gtr030.pdf}}</ref>\n\n[[Fisher (animal)|Fisher]]s are known to occasionally hunt Canada lynxes in the northeastern United States; a study in northern [[Maine]] identified predation by fishers as the leading cause of Canada lynx mortality over 12 years, though it did not appear to affect population growth in the lynxes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McLellan |first1=S. R. |last2=Vashon |first2=J. H. |last3=Johnson |first3=E. L. |last4=Crowley |first4=S. M. |last5=Vashon |first5=A. D. |title=Fisher predation on Canada lynx in the Northeastern United States |journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management |date=2018 |volume=82 |issue=8 |pages=1775\u20131783 |doi=10.1002/jwmg.21538}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Learn|first=J.R.|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2018/09/Weasel-like-fishers-prey-on-Canada-Lynx-in-Maine-news/|title=Small weasel-like animals are taking down big cats|date=28 September 2018|website=[[National Geographic]]|publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]|accessdate = 16 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe Canada lynx is known to host several [[Parasitism|parasite]]s including ''[[Cylicospirura felineus]]'', ''[[Taenia (cestode)|Taenia]]'' species, ''[[Toxocara cati]]'', ''[[Toxascaris leonina]]'' and ''[[Troglostrongylus wilsoni]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=van Zyll de Jong |first1=C. G. |title=Parasites of the Canada lynx, ''Felis (Lynx) canadensis'' (Kerr) |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |date=1966 |volume=44 |issue=4 |pages=499\u2013509 |doi=10.1139/z66-054|pmid=5944283 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=J. D. |last2=Addison |first2=E. M. |last3=Joachim |first3=D. G. |last4=Smith |first4=L. M. |last5=Quinn |first5=N. W. S. |title=Helminth parasites of Canada lynx (''Felis canadensis'') from northern Ontario |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |date=1986 |volume=64 |issue=2 |pages=358\u2013364 |doi=10.1139/z86-057}}</ref> Canada lynxes could have played a role in the transmission of the [[zoonosis|zoonotic]] parasite ''[[Toxoplasma gondii]]'' to the [[Inuit]] in North America.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reiling |first1=S. J. |last2=Dixon |first2=B. R. |title=''Toxoplasma gondii'': How an Amazonian parasite became an Inuit health issue |journal= Canada Communicable Disease Report|date=2019 |volume=45 |issue=7/8 |pages=183\u2013190 |doi=10.14745/ccdr.v45i78a03 |pmid=31355827|pmc=6615440 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simon |first1=A. |last2=Poulin |first2=M. B. |last3=Rousseau |first3=A. N. |last4=Dubey |first4=J. P. |last5=Ogden |first5=N. H. |title=Spatiotemporal dynamics of Toxoplasma gondii infection in Canadian lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') in Western Quebec, Canada |journal=Journal of Wildlife Diseases |date=2013 |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=39\u201348 |doi=10.7589/2012-02-048|pmid=23307370 }}</ref> A study in 2019 identified a [[gammaherpesvirus]] species in the Canada lynx for the first time. The study discovered a novel [[percavirus]], named LcaGHV1, in [[spleen]] samples of Canada lynxes from Maine and Newfoundland.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hendrikse |first1=L. D. |last2=Kambli |first2=A. |last3=Kayko |first3=C. |last4=Canuti |first4=M. |last5=Rodrigues |first5=B. |last6=Stevens |first6=B. |last7=Vashon |first7=J. |last8=Lang |first8=A. S. |last9=Needle |first9=D. B. |last10=Troyer |first10=R. M. |title=Identification of a novel gammaherpesvirus in Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') |journal=Viruses |date=2019 |volume=11 |issue=4 |pages=363 |doi=10.3390/v11040363|pmid=31010021 |pmc=6520957 }}</ref> \n\n=== Relationship with the snowshoe hare ===\n[[File:Milliers fourrures vendues en environ 90 ans odum 1953 en.jpg|right|upright=2|thumb|Numbers of [[snowshoe hare]]s (''Lepus americanus'', yellow, background) and Canada lynx (black line, foreground) furs sold to the [[Hudson's Bay Company]]]]\nA [[Generalist and specialist species|specialist predator]], the Canada lynx depends heavily on snowshoe hares for food.<ref name=Hunter/> Snowshoe hare populations in Alaska and central Canada undergo cyclic rises and falls\u2014at times the population densities can fall from as high as {{convert|2,300|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}} to as low as {{convert|12|/sqkm|/sqmi|abbr=on}}. Consequently, a period of hare scarcity occurs every 8 to 11 years. An example of a prey-predator cycle, the cyclic variations in snowshoe hare populations significantly affect the numbers of their predators\u2014lynxes and [[coyote]]s\u2014in the region. When the hare populations plummet, lynxes tend to move to areas with more hares, and tend to not produce litters; as the numbers of the hare increase, so does the population of the lynx.<ref name=\"Brand1979\">{{cite journal|last1=Brand|first1=C.J.|last2=Keith|first2=L.B.|title=Lynx demography during a snowshoe hare decline in Alberta|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1979|volume=43|issue=4|pages=827\u2013849|doi=10.2307/3808267|jstor=3808267}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=M. |last2=Boutin |first2=S. |last3=Krebs |first3=C.J. |last4=Hofer |first4=E.J. |title=Numerical responses of coyotes and lynx to the snowshoe hare cycle |journal=Oikos |date=1997 |volume=80 |issue=1 |pages=150\u2013162 |doi=10.2307/3546526|jstor=3546526 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ward |first1=R.M.P. |last2=Krebs |first2=C.J. |title=Behavioural responses of lynx to declining snowshoe hare abundance |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |date=1985 |volume=63 |issue=12 |pages=2817\u20132824 |doi=10.1139/z85-421}}</ref> In northern Canada, the abundance of lynxes can be estimated from the records kept of the number caught each year for their fur; records have been kept by the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] and [[Government of Canada|Canadian government]] since the 1730s.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Weinstein |first=M.S. |year=1977|title=Hares, lynx, and trappers |journal= The American Naturalist|volume= 111|issue=980 |pages=806\u20138 |doi=10.1086/283212 |jstor=2460337}}</ref> These cycles have been cited as one of the few examples of the [[Lotka-Volterra equations|Lotka\u2013Volterra predator\u2013prey equations]], caused by the interplay of three major factors\u2014food, predation and social interaction.<ref name=\"krebs2001\">{{cite journal |last1=Krebs |first1=C.J. |last2=Boonstra |first2=R. |last3=Boutin |first3=S. |last4=Sinclair |first4=A.R.E. |title=What drives the 10-year cycle of snowshoe hares?: The ten-year cycle of snowshoe hares\u2014one of the most striking features of the boreal forest\u2014 is a product of the interaction between predation and food supplies, as large-scale experiments in the Yukon have demonstrated |journal=BioScience |date=2001 |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=25\u201335 |doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2001)051[0025:WDTYCO]2.0.CO;2|url=https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article-pdf/51/1/25/26890541/51-1-25.pdf}}</ref> A study involving statistical modelling of the interspecific relations of the snowshoe hare, the plant species it feeds on and its predators (including the Canada lynx) suggested that while the demographics of the lynx depend primarily on the hare, the hare's dynamics depend both on the plant species in its diet and predators, of which the Canada lynx is just one.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stenseth |first1=N.C. |last2=Falck |first2=W. |last3=Bj\u00f8rnstad |first3=O.N. |last4=Krebs |first4=C.J. |title=Population regulation in snowshoe hare and Canadian lynx: Asymmetric food web configurations between hare and lynx |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=1997 |volume=94 |issue=10 |pages=5147\u201352 |doi=10.1073/pnas.94.10.5147 |pmid=9144205 |pmc=24646 |bibcode=1997PNAS...94.5147C |url=https://www.pnas.org/content/pnas/94/10/5147.full.pdf}}</ref> Environmental factors such as forest fires, precipitation and snowfall might also significantly affect this prey-predator cycle.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fox |first1=J.F. |title=Forest fires and the snowshoe hare-Canada lynx cycle |journal=Oecologia |date=1978 |volume=31 |issue=3 |pages=349\u2013374 |doi=10.1007/BF00346252}}</ref>\n\n===Home ranges===\n[[File:Canada lynx (6002291242).jpg|thumb|Lynxes are typically solitary with minimal social bonds.]]\nCanada lynxes establish [[home range]]s that vary widely in size, depending upon the method of measurement. The two common methods are examining the tracks of the lynx on snow (snow-tracking) and [[Wildlife radio telemetry|radio telemetry]]; snow-tracking generally gives smaller sizes for home ranges. Studies based on snow-tracking have estimated home range sizes of {{convert|11.1|\u2013|49.5|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, while those based on radio telemetry have given the area between {{convert|8|and|783|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=lox/> Like other cats, Canada lynxes [[Territorial marking|scent-mark]] their ranges by spraying urine and depositing faeces on snow or tree stumps and other prominent sites in and around their range.<ref name=Sunquist/>\n\nFactors such as availability of prey (primarily snowshoe hare), density of lynxes and the topography of the habitat determine the shape and size of the home range.<ref name=lox/> Studies have tried to correlate the abundance of snowshoe hares in an area with the sizes of lynx home ranges in that area. A 1985 study showed that the mean size of home ranges trebled\u2014from {{convert|13.2|to|39.2|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}\u2014when the density of hares fell from {{convert|14.7|to|1|/ha|/acre|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite journal|last1=Ward|first1=R.M.P.|last2=Krebs|first2=C.J.|title=Behavioural responses of lynx to declining snowshoe hare abundance|journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology|date=1985|volume=63|issue=12|pages=2817\u201324|doi=10.1139/z85-421}}</ref> However, a few other studies have reported different responses from lynxes at times of prey scarcity; some lynxes do not show any changes in their ranges, while others may resort to hunting in small areas, occupying small home ranges.<ref name=lox/> Canada lynxes generally do not leave their home ranges frequently, though limited prey availability can force lynxes to disperse or expand their ranges.<ref name=Poole1995>{{cite journal|last1=Poole|first1=K.G.|title=Spatial organization of a lynx population|journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology|date=1995|volume=73|issue=4|pages=632\u201341|doi=10.1139/z95-074}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Poole|first1=K.G.|title=Dispersal patterns of lynx in the Northwest Territories|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|date=1997|volume=61|issue=2|pages=497\u2013505|doi=10.2307/3802607|jstor=3802607}}</ref>\n\nMales tend to occupy larger ranges than do females; for instance, data from a 1980 radio telemetric analysis in [[Minnesota]] showed that home ranges of males spread over {{convert|145|\u2013|243|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, while those of females covered {{convert|51|\u2013|122|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mech|first1=L.D.|title=Age, sex, reproduction, and spatial organization of lynxes colonizing Northeastern Minnesota|journal=Journal of Mammalogy|date=1980|volume=61|issue=2|pages=261\u20137|jstor=1380047|doi=10.2307/1380047}}</ref> In another radio telemetric study in 1985 in [[Montana]], male home ranges averaged {{convert|122|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}} and those of females averaged {{convert|43.1|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Brainerd|first=S.M.|title=Reproductive ecology of bobcats and lynx in western Montana|type=M.Sc. thesis |publisher=[[University of Montana]]|date=1985|pages=1\u201385}}</ref> In a study in the southern [[Northwest Territories]], ranges of individuals of opposite sexes were found to overlap extensively, while the ranges of individuals of the same sex hardly coincided. The study suggested that individuals do not show any significant tendency to avoid or mingle with one another, and thus only passively defend their ranges.<ref name=Poole1995/> Female home ranges contract in size when the females have offspring to take care of, and expand to their original size at the time of weaning.<ref name=ruggiero/>\n\nA [[Genetics|genetic]] study showed that lynxes at the periphery of a population, given their smaller numbers and greater susceptibility to variations in the range, face more difficulty in breeding with lynxes toward the centre of the population and hence show lower [[genetic variability]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schwartz |first1=M.K. |last2=Mills |first2=L.S. |last3=Ortega |first3=Y. |last4=Ruggiero |first4=L.F. |last5=Allendorf |first5=F.W. |title=Landscape location affects genetic variation of Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') |journal=Molecular Ecology |date=2003 |volume=12 |issue=7 |pages=1807\u201316 |doi=10.1046/j.1365-294X.2003.01878.x|pmid=12803633 }}</ref>\n\n===Diet and hunting===\n[[File:Snowshoe Hare (6187109754).jpg|thumb|left|[[Snowshoe hare]], the primary prey of the Canada lynx]]\nThe Canada lynx preys primarily and almost exclusively on the snowshoe hare. These hares comprise 35\u201397% of their diet; the proportion varies by the season and the abundance of hares.<ref name=Hunter/> However, at times when the numbers of the hare drop, lynxes will include other animals in their diet\u2014such as ducks, [[grouse]], moles, [[ptarmigan]], [[red squirrel]]s, voles and young [[ungulate]]s ([[Dall's sheep]], [[mule deer]] and [[boreal woodland caribou|caribou]])\u2014though snowshoe hares continue to be the primary component. The Canada lynx tends to be less selective in summer and autumn, adding small mammals as a minor component of their diet besides the hare. The reason behind this is unclear\u2014it could be due to greater abundance of alternate prey, or reduced success in hunting hares.<ref name=ruggiero/> A study in Alaska found that lynxes played a role in the decrease in populations of [[red fox]], caribou and Dall's sheep when hares were very low in number.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stephenson |first1=R.O. |last2=Grangaard |first2=D.V. |last3=Burch |first3=J. |title=Lynx, ''Felis lynx'', predation on red foxes, ''Vulpes vulpes'', caribou, ''Rangifer tarandus'', and Dall sheep, ''Ovis dalli'', in Alaska |journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist |date=1991 |volume=105 |pages=255\u201362 |url=http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/static/home/library/pdfs/wildlife/propubs/91_stephenson_etal_lynx_predation_redfoxes_caribou_dallsheep_ak.pdf}}</ref> Canada lynxes ingest {{convert|0.6|\u2013|1.2|kg|lb}} of food everyday.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter/> Lynxes have also been reported feeding occasionally on [[Succulent plant|succulent]] [[sedge]]s and grasses.<ref name=yukongov/>\n\nCanadian lynxes hunt around twilight or at night, the time when snowshoe hares tend to be active.<ref name=Hunter/> Lynxes rely on their vision and sense of hearing to locate prey.<ref name=Nowak/> The lynx will roam or wait (in what researchers often term \"ambush beds\") on certain trails where snowshoe hares gather, pounce on a hare and kill it by a bite on its head, throat or the nape of its neck.<ref name=ruggiero/> Sometimes a chase of around ten bounds may be necessary to trap the prey. The lynx is assisted by its [[Stereopsis|stereoscopic vision]] in detecting prey and measuring distances. Staying in cover while hunting helps the lynx conserve energy in its frigid habitat by avoiding unnecessary movement.<ref name=yukongov/> Young ungulates are given a throat bite to suffocate them to death. The lynx may eat its kill immediately or cache it in snow or leaves to eat it over the next few days.<ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter/><ref name=ruggiero/> Studies suggest success in hunting hares depends heavily on the distance between the lynx and the hare when the lynx starts chasing it and their relative speeds, which in turn depends on the hunting prowess of the lynx, the alertness of the hare and the vegetation cover among other factors.<ref name=Sunquist/> Lynxes will occasionally hunt together, though studies differ on how this affects the hunting success rate compared to when an individual hunts alone.<ref name=ruggiero/> In fact, they may hunt in groups when hares are scarce.<ref name = dono98/> [[Scavenger|Scavenging]] is common in Canada lynxes; they will take ungulates killed by the cold or vehicles.<ref name=Hunter/>\n[[File:Lynx-canadensis.jpg|thumb|right|A lynx stalking its prey]]\nBoth coyotes and Canada lynxes are major predators of the snowshoe hare. A study showed that compared to lynxes, the feet of coyotes sink deeper in the snow due to their smaller size and hence a larger body mass to foot area ratio, prompting them to ambush their prey instead of chasing it like lynxes often do.<ref name=\"murray1991\">{{cite journal |last1=Murray |first1=D.L. |last2=Boutin |first2=S. |title=The influence of snow on lynx and coyote movements: does morphology affect behavior? |journal=Oecologia |date=1991 |volume=88 |issue=4 |pages=463\u20139 |doi=10.1007/BF00317707|pmid=28312614 |bibcode=1991Oecol..88..463M }}</ref> A study of the two species in southwest [[Yukon Territory]] showed that when the numbers of the hare increased, both predators killed more hares than were necessary for their subsistence; lynxes need to kill 0.4 to 0.5 hare per day to meet their energy requirements, but were observed to kill 1.2 hares per day during this period. Coyotes, with a success rate of 36.9%, emerged as more successful hunters than lynxes that succeeded in 28.7% of their hunts; however this may have resulted from the greater number of adult coyotes in the studied population. Lynxes rarely cached their kills, unlike coyotes, and this may have led to incomplete consumption of some kills. During the cyclic decrease in snowshoe hare numbers, both predators hunted for the same time period as they did when hares were abundant, but lynxes killed more hares than they did earlier. Moreover, lynxes supplemented their diet with red squirrels.<ref name=ODonoghue/><ref name=dono98>{{cite journal |last1=O'Donoghue |first1=M. |last2=Boutin |first2=S. |last3=Krebs |first3=C.J. |last4=Murray|first4=D.L. |last5=Hofer |first5=E.J.| title=Behavioural responses of coyote and lynx to the snowshoe hare cycle |journal=Oikos |date=1998 |volume=82 |issue=1 |pages=169\u201383 |doi=10.2307/3546927|jstor=3546927 }}</ref>\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Canada Lynx Mom and Kitten (15250932421).jpg|thumb|left|A juvenile with its mother]]\n\nThe mating season is roughly a month long, from March to early April. Urine marking and mating calls are part of [[Display (zoology)|display behaviour]], and increases the interaction between individuals of opposite sexes. Females can be [[Induced ovulation (animals)|induced ovulators]] when the availability of mates is low, or spontaneous ovulators when several mates are available. Females have only a single [[estrus cycle]]; estrus lasts for three to five days in captivity.<ref name=Sunquist /> Individuals have been observed making long wailing vocalizations, probably as mating calls.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Slough |first1=B.G. |last2=Mowat |first2=G. |title=Some observations on the natural history and behaviour of the Canada Lynx, ''Lynx canadensis'' |journal=Canadian Field Naturalist |date=1998 |volume=112 |issue=1 |pages=32-36 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Brian_Slough/publication/268872103_Some_observations_on_the_natural_history_and_behaviour_of_the_Canada_Lynx_Lynx_canadensis/links/547a2cbc0cf293e2da2b5e05.pdf}}</ref> Before birth, the female prepares a maternal den, usually in very thick brush, and typically inside thickets of shrubs, trees or woody debris.<ref name=Kaufman/><ref>{{cite journal |last=Slough |first=B. G. |year=1999 |title=Characteristics of Canada lynx, ''Lynx canadensis'', maternal dens and denning habitat |journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist |volume=113 |issue=4 |pages=605\u2013608}}</ref> The home range of the expecting female shrinks and her activity at the den site increases.<ref name=Sunquist/>\n\nAfter a gestational period of two to three months, a litter of one to eight kittens is born.<ref name=Sunquist /> Lynx reproductive cycles and litter sizes have been observed to vary with prey availability; litter size would typically contract in years of snowshoe hare decline (along with high infant mortality rates), and increase when hares were abundant.<ref name=\"breitenmoser\">{{cite journal |last1=Breitenmoser |first1=U. |last2=Slough |first2=B.G. |last3=Breitenmoser-W\u00fcrsten |first3=C. |title=Predators of cyclic prey: is the Canada lynx a victim or profiteer of the snowshoe hare cycle? |journal=Oikos |date=1993 |volume=66 |issue=3 |pages=551\u2013554 |doi=10.2307/3544952|jstor=3544952 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Slough |first1=B.G. |last2=Mowat |first2=G. |title=Lynx population dynamics in an untrapped refugium |journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management |date=1996 |volume=60 |issue=4 |pages=946\u2013961 |doi=10.2307/3802397}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=M.|first1=Garth |last2=Slough |first2=B.G. |last3=Boutin |first3=S.|title=Lynx recruitment during a snowshoe hare population peak and decline in southwest Yukon |journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management |date=1996 |volume=60 |issue=2 |pages=441\u2013452 |doi=10.2307/3802247}}</ref> Kittens weigh from {{convert|175|to|235|g|oz|abbr=on}} at birth, and initially have grayish buff fur with black markings. They are blind for the first 14 days, and [[weaning|weaned]] at 12 weeks. Most births occur from May to July. Kittens leave the den after about five weeks, and begin hunting at between seven and nine months of age. They leave the mother at around ten months, as the next breeding season begins, but do not reach the full adult size until around two years old. Female offspring typically settle in home ranges close to their mothers and remain in contact with them for life, while male offspring move far from their mother's range. Females reach sexual maturity at ten months, although they often delay breeding for another year, whereas males reach maturity at two or three years. Canada lynxes have been reported to live for up to 16 years in wild, though most do not make it beyond 10 years; in captivity the lifespan may be as long as 27 years.<ref name=Sunquist /><ref name=Hunter/>\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\n[[File:Young Lynx spotted west of Drayton Valley Ab - panoramio.jpg|thumb|Canada lynxes prefer dense [[boreal forest]]s.]]\nThe Canada lynx occurs predominantly in dense [[Taiga|boreal forest]]s, and its range heavily coincides with that of the snowshoe hare. Canada lynxes generally avoid open areas despite good prey availability; they face difficulty surviving in heavily logged areas and agricultural land, though they can thrive well in deforested areas which have been left to regenerate for 15 years or more. In the past, the lynx occurred from the northern United States (in 24 States), possibly up to the [[Rocky Mountains]] in [[New Mexico]], to the [[tree line]] in the Arctic through coniferous forests in Alaska and Canada. The lynx continues to occur in most of Alaska and its erstwhile range in Canada. In the United States, the lynx occurs in the  [[Blue Mountains (Pacific Northwest)|Blue Mountains]], [[Cascade Range]] and southern Rocky Mountains, [[Great Lakes region]] and [[New England]]. The lynx has been successfully reintroduced in [[Colorado]], where it had become extinct in the 1970s. Canada lynxes have been recorded up to an elevation of {{convert|4310|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=Sunquist/><ref name=Hunter/>\n\nA Canada lynx was shot near [[Newton Abbot]] in the United Kingdom in 1903 after it attacked two dogs. The animal remained unidentified at the time and was preserved by [[Bristol Museum and Art Gallery]], and was finally identified in a 2014 study. The researchers concluded that it had probably been captive for some time, perhaps as an [[exotic pet]] or part of a travelling menagerie, but may have survived for a substantial period after escaping. They considered it \"the earliest recorded example of an exotic cat on the loose in the UK\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Blake |first1=M. |last2=Naish |first2=D. |last3=Larson |first3=G. |last4=King |first4=C.L. |last5=Nowell |first5=G. |last6=Sakamoto |first6=M. |last7=Barnett |first7=R. |title=Multidisciplinary investigation of a \u2018British big cat\u2019: a lynx killed in southern England c. 1903 |journal=Historical Biology |date=2013 |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=441\u2013448 |doi=10.1080/08912963.2013.785541}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-22263874|title='Big cat' Canada lynx was on the loose in UK in 1903|last=Morelle|first=R.|date=24 April 2013|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Postmedia News |title=That 'British big cat' called England's Loch Ness Monster? Its legend was fuelled by Canadian lynx, study says |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/that-british-big-cat-thats-like-englands-loch-ness-monster-its-legend-was-fuelled-by-a-canadian-lynx-study-says |accessdate=9 April 2020 |publisher=National Post |date=26 April 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mohan |first1=G. |title=British big cat theory gets bump from lynx link |url=https://www.latimes.com/science/la-xpm-2013-apr-24-la-sci-sn-big-cats-britain-20130424-story.html |accessdate=9 April 2020 |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=24 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Threats and conservation ==\n[[File:Felis lynx canadensis (Canadian lynx) fur skin back.jpg|thumb|left|Canada lynxes are trapped for their fur.]]\nCanada lynxes are trapped in specific periods or seasons for fur trade in most of Alaska and Canada; hunting seasons and quotas are set based on population data. Even without regulations in place, the lynx-hare cycles and the distribution of the lynx have remained unaffected over the last century. In eastern Canada the lynx is threatened by competition with the [[eastern coyote]], whose numbers in the region have rose in the last few decades. Habitat loss is the main threat in the [[contiguous United States]], while trapping is a relatively insignificant cause of mortality. Hybridization between Canada lynxes and bobcats has been reported in the southern periphery of the range, and does not appear to be a threat to Canada lynxes.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Homyack, J.A. |year=2008|title=Canada Lynx-Bobcat (''Lynx canadensis \u00d7 L.rufus'') hybrids at the southern periphery of lynx range in Maine, Minnesota and New Brunswick|url=http://www.fs.fed.us/rm/pubs_other/rmrs_2008_homyack_j001.pdf|journal= American Midland Naturalist |volume=159|pages=504\u2013508|doi=10.1674/0003-0031(2008)159[504:CLLCLR]2.0.CO;2|issue=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Schwartz, M.K. | year = 2004 | title = Hybridization between Canada Lynx and bobcats: genetic results and management implications| journal = Conservation Genetics | volume = 5 | pages = 349\u2013355 | doi = 10.1023/B:COGE.0000031141.47148.8b | issue = 3|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/225195035_Hybridization_Between_Canada_Lynx_and_Bobcats_Genetic_Results_and_Management_Implications }}</ref>\n\nThe Canada lynx is abundant over its broad range, and is not significantly threatened by its legal use in the international fur trade since more than two centuries. Therefore, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]] (IUCN) classifies the Canada lynx as [[Least Concern]]. However, populations are relatively lower in the southern half of the range and are protected from killing for fur trade. The lynx is listed as Endangered in [[New Brunswick]] and [[Nova Scotia]].<ref name=iucn/> On March 24, 2000, the [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]] (USFWS) issued its Final Rule, which designated the Canada lynx a Threatened Species in 14 contiguous United States.<ref name=\"FedReg\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-2000-03-24/pdf/00-7145.pdf|title=Endangered and Threatened Wildlife and Plants; Determination of Threatened Status for the Contiguous U.S. Distinct Population Segment of the Canada Lynx and Related Rule |page=16051\u201316086|journal=Federal Register|volume= 65|issue= 58 |date= 24 March 2000|publisher=Department of the Interior, Fish and Wildlife Service}}</ref> In 2005, the USFWS demarcated six major areas for revival where lynx populations had been reported in the past two decades: northern Maine and [[New Hampshire]], northeastern Minnesota, northwestern Montana and northeastern [[Idaho]], the [[Kettle River Range]] and the \"Wedge area\" between the [[Kettle River (Columbia River tributary)|Kettle]] and [[Columbia River|Columbia]] rivers of [[Washington (state)|Washington]], the northern Cascade Range of Washington, and the [[Greater Yellowstone]] area of [[Wyoming]], Montana and Idaho.<ref name=iucn/> By 2010, after an 11-year effort, the lynx had been successfully reintroduced into Colorado. The initial introduction was in the [[San Juan Mountains]] in southwestern Colorado, but self-sustaining populations were established throughout the south-central Colorado Rockies as far north as [[Summit County, Colorado|Summit County]].<ref>{{cite report|title=Success of the Colorado Division of Wildlife\u2019s lynx reintroduction program|url=http://wildlife.state.co.us/NR/rdonlyres/6EBDE944-FF9A-4CE4-894D-8547184CB8BA/0/ColoradoLynxReintroductionAssessment_090710.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718225119/http://wildlife.state.co.us/NR/rdonlyres/6EBDE944-FF9A-4CE4-894D-8547184CB8BA/0/ColoradoLynxReintroductionAssessment_090710.pdf|date=18 July 2011|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=dead|pages=1\u20134|publisher=Colorado Parks and Wildlife}}</ref> A 2012 study showed that numbers have improved in the northeastern United States;<ref>{{cite report|last1=Vashon |first1=J. |last2=McLellan |first2=S. |last3=Crowley |first3=S. |last4=Meehan |first4=A. |last5=Laustsen |first5=K. |title=Canada Lynx Assessment |date=2012 |pages=1\u2013107 |url=https://www.maine.gov/ifw/docs/species_planning/mammals/canadalynx/Lynx%20Assessment%202012_Final.pdf |publisher=Maine Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife Research and Assessment Section |location=Maine}}</ref> however a 2008 study showed lynx populations were not doing well in Washington due to [[habitat fragmentation]]. A 2017 study reported increasing numbers in many areas in the United States.<ref>{{cite report|author1=[[US Fish and Wildlife Service]] |title=Species Status Assessment for the Canada lynx (''Lynx canadensis'') Contiguous United States Distinct Population Segment. Version 1.0 |date=2017 |pages=1-300 |url=https://www.fws.gov/mountain-prairie/es/species/mammals/lynx/SSA2018/01112018_SSA_Report_CanadaLynx.pdf |publisher=Contiguous United States Distinct Population Segment |location=Colorado}}</ref> In January 2018, the USFWS declared that the Canada lynx no longer needed special protections in the United States following measures to preserve their populations, and their \"Threatened\" status may be revoked in the future.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ktuu.com/content/news/US-says-snow-loving-lynx-no-longer-need-special-protection-468986383.html|title=US says snow-loving lynx no longer need special protection|date=12 January 2018|author=Associated Press|publisher=KTUU-TV|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Mammals}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|Lynx canadensis}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lynx canadensis}}\n* [http://www.catsg.org/index.php?id=97 Species portrait Canada lynx; IUCN/SSC Cat Specialist Group]\n* [http://ecos.fws.gov/speciesProfile/SpeciesReport.do?spcode=A073 U.S. Fish & Wildlife \"Species Profile\" and lynx article index]\n* [http://www.nrri.umn.edu/lynx/ Canada lynx research] at the [[University of Minnesota Duluth|University of Minnesota \u2013 Duluth]]\n* [https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/359/2/krebs.2001%20bioscience.pdf What Drives the 10-year Cycle of Snowshoe Hares?]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100714115216/http://www.voiceforthewild.org/mbnf/pubs/rdls/rdls.html Medicine Bow National Forest (A Habitat of the Canada Lynx)]\u2014Biodiversity Conservation Alliance\n* [http://www.rmrs.nau.edu/wildlife/forest_carnivores/lynx/ Forest Service Canada lynx research]\n\n{{Carnivora|Fe.}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q146457}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lynx, Canada}}\n[[Category:Arctic land animals]]\n[[Category:Ecological experiments]]\n[[Category:ESA threatened species]]\n[[Category:Fauna of New England]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Great Lakes region (North America)]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Plains-Midwest (United States)]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Rocky Mountains]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Western United States]]\n[[Category:Felids of North America]]\n[[Category:Lynx]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1792]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Canada]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Sainsf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePhysical characteristics:ordering refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canada_lynx"}
{"title_page": "Holby City", "text_new": "{{Short description|British medical drama series}}\n{{About|the British television series|the fictional city|Holby}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Holby City\n| image              = HolbyCity2015.jpg\n| genre              = [[Medical drama]]\n| creator            = [[Tony McHale]] <br> [[Mal Young]]\n| starring           = [[List of Holby City characters|Present and former cast]]\n| language           = English\n| country            = United Kingdom\n| num_series         = 22\n| num_episodes       = 1,023 <!-- As of Wednesday 15 April 2020; update count and date weekly after episode has aired -->\n| list_episodes      = List of Holby City episodes\n| executive_producer = '''Currently:''' <br> Simon Harper (2017\u2013) <br> '''Previously:''' <br> [[Mal Young]] (1999\u20132004) <br> [[Johnathan Young]] (1999, 2011\u20132013) <br> [[Kathleen Hutchison]] (2002\u20132004)<br> [[Richard Stokes (producer)|Richard Stokes]] (2004\u20132006) <br>[[Tony McHale]] (2006\u20132010) <br> Belinda Campbell (2010\u20132011) <br> Oliver Kent (2013\u20132017)\n| camera             = [[Single-camera setup]]\n| company            = [[BBC]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|1999|1|12|df=y}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| related            = ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'' (1986\u2013present)<br />''[[HolbyBlue]]'' (2007\u201308)\n| website            = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006mhd6\n| channel            = [[BBC One]] <br> [[BBC One HD]] (2010\u2013)\n}}\n\n'''''Holby City''''' (styled as '''''HOLBY CI<sup>+</sup>Y''''') is a British medical drama television series that airs weekly on [[BBC One]]. The series was created by [[Tony McHale]] and [[Mal Young]] as a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] from the established BBC medical drama ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'', and premiered on 12 January 1999. It is set in the same hospital as ''Casualty'' in the fictional city of [[Holby]], and featured occasional crossovers of characters and plots with both ''Casualty'' (which featured dedicated episodes broadcast as ''[[Casualty@Holby City]]'') and the show's 2007 [[police procedural]] spin-off ''[[HolbyBlue]]''.\n\nIts first executive producers were Young and [[Johnathan Young]], who were succeeded by [[Kathleen Hutchison]] from 2002 to 2004, [[Richard Stokes (producer)|Richard Stokes]] from 2004 to 2006, McHale from 2006 to 2010, Belinda Campbell from 2010 to 2011, Johnathan Young from 2011 to 2013, Oliver Kent from 2013 to 2017 and Simon Harper from 2017. ''Holby City'' airs once a week, all year round, and each series now contains 52 episodes.\n\nThe  show follows the lives of medical and ancillary staff at the fictional [[Holby City Hospital]]. It began with eleven main characters in its [[Holby City (series 1)|first series]], all of whom have since left the show. New main characters have been both written in and out of the series since, with a core of around fifteen main actors employed on the serial at any given time. In casting the first series, Young sought out actors who were already well known in the television industry, something which has continued throughout the show's history, with cast members including [[Patsy Kensit]], [[Jane Asher]], [[Robert Powell]], [[Ade Edmondson]] and [[John Michie]].\n\nMcHale was the show's lead writer for several years, and was the first British writer ever to become the showrunner of a major prime time drama. Under his tenure as executive producer, attempts were made at modernising the programme and appealing to a younger audience by taking on the [[filmizing]] technique and introducing musical montage segments into each episode. Twenty-one series of ''Holby City'' have aired with a [[Holby City (series 22)|twenty-second]] currently on a transmission break. The show has run for over 1000 hour-long episodes. It is filmed at the [[BBC Elstree Centre]] in [[Hertfordshire]], and has featured special episodes filmed on location abroad. From October 2010, ''Holby City'' moved to [[High-definition television|high definition]] broadcasting.\n\n''Holby City'' has attracted comparisons to other medical dramas, often unfavourable, and figures within the television and entertainment industry including [[Broadcasting Standards Commission]] director Paul Bolt have accused the BBC of squandering the television [[licence fee]] on the programme. The series employs a team of researchers to ensure medical accuracy, and utilises surgeons from different disciplines to check scripts. Cast members are taught to perform basic medical procedures, and given the opportunity to spend time on real hospital wards for research. ''Holby City'' has, however, been criticised for its lack of realism, with the [[British Medical Association]] denouncing its portrayal of organ donation and unrealistic impression of resuscitation, and an [[accident and emergency]] nurse at the 2008 [[Royal College of Nursing]] conference accusing the show of fostering unrealistic expectations of the NHS and fuelling compensation culture.\n\n''Holby City'' [[List of awards and nominations received by Holby City|has been nominated for over 100 television awards]], of which it has won ten: the 2008 [[British Academy Television Award]] for Best Continuing Drama, one BEFFTA Award, two [[Ethnic Multicultural Media Academy|Ethnic Multicultural Media Awards]], two Music Video and Screen Awards, and four [[Screen Nation]] Awards. The show's [[Holby City (series 1)|first series]] averaged 9.27&nbsp;million viewers, but apart from a rise in its [[Holby City (series 5)|fifth series]], ratings declined year-on-year until 2009, with the [[Holby City (series 11)|eleventh series]] averaging 5.44&nbsp;million viewers. The [[Holby City (series 12)|twelfth series]] saw a small rise to 5.62&nbsp;million. Later series have consistently drawn over 4&nbsp;million viewers per week.\n\n==Production==\nThe show began with only eleven main characters in its [[Holby City (series 1)|first series]], all of whom have since left the show. New main characters have been both written in and out of the series since, with a core of fifteen to twenty main actors employed on the serial at any given time. In casting the first series, Young sought out actors who were already well known in the television industry, something which has continued throughout the show's history, with cast members including [[Patsy Kensit]], [[Jane Asher]], [[Robert Powell]], [[Adrian Edmondson]], [[Alex Walkinshaw]] and [[Jemma Redgrave]].\n\nMcHale was the show's lead writer for several years, and was the first British writer ever to become the \"showrunner\" of a major prime time drama. Under his tenure as executive producer, attempts were made at modernising the programme and appealing to a younger audience by taking on the [[filmising]] technique and introducing musical montage segments into each episode. Twenty complete series of ''Holby City'' have aired, and an twenty-first began airing in January 2019. The show has run for over 600 hour-long episodes. It is filmed in studios at the BBC Elstree Centre in Hertfordshire, with the 1960s office building Neptune House being used for multiple exteriors and interiors in the series. It has occasionally featured special episodes filmed on location abroad. From October 2010, ''Holby City'' moved to [[High-definition television|high definition]] broadcasting.\n\nIn September 2016, as part of the broadcaster's Compete Or Compare Strategy, the BBC confirmed the show would be one of the first put up for tender.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Austin|first1=Jamie|title=BBC names first shows in new competitive tendering plan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2016/BBC-first-shows-competitive-tendering|website=[[BBC]]|accessdate=19 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161027133911/http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2016/BBC-first-shows-competitive-tendering|archivedate=27 October 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the tender released in October, it was confirmed the contract, open to independent producers and [[BBC Studios]], would be for 3 series of a minimum 50 episodes per series, delivered from December 2017 with no break in transmission and produced from the existing production base at [[BBC Elstree Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Invitation to Tender (ITT) |url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/commissioning/site/bbc-content-invitation-to-tender-holby-city-october-2016.pdf |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=19 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020052444/http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/commissioning/site/bbc-content-invitation-to-tender-holby-city-october-2016.pdf |archivedate=20 October 2016 |df= }}</ref> BBC Studios was announced as the winning bidder and will continue to produce the show through to 2020.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC - BBC Studios awarded Holby City tender - Commissioning|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/commissioning/news/articles/bbc-studios-awarded-holby-city-tender-march-2017|accessdate=14 December 2017|work=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Development===\n''Holby City'' was created by [[Tony McHale]] and [[Mal Young]] as a spin-off from the BBC medical drama ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'', which is set in the [[emergency department]] of the fictional Holby City Hospital.<ref name=\"digital spy1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holbycity/news/a191337/holby-citys-exec-producer-stands-down.html |title='Holby City's exec producer stands down |last=Green |first=Kris |date=14 December 2009 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=12 January 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17Zw9V1?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/news/a191337/holby-citys-exec-producer-stands-down.html |archivedate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/FILM+of+the+season;+BABE,+Christmas+Day,+BBC1+7pm.-a060945126|title=Film of the season; Babe, Christmas Day, BBC1 7&nbsp;pm.|date=19 December 1998|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|accessdate=10 October 2010|location=Glasgow, Scotland}}</ref> Young wanted to explore what happened to patients treated in ''Casualty'' once they were taken away to the hospital's surgical wards.<ref name=\"JT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Life's+sweet+off+the+Street;+Exit+Coronation+Street+stage+left,+enter...-a060364526 |title=Life's sweet off the Street |last=Taylor |first=Jim |date=2 January 1999 |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]] |accessdate=23 April 2010 |location=Glasgow, Scotland |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17dHnqX?url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/403.htm |archivedate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> While ''Casualty''{{'s}} scope is limited to \"accident of the week\" storylines about patients entering hospital, ''Holby City'' allowed the possibility of storylines about long-term care, rather than immediate life and death decisions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Drama+that+gets+right+to+the+heart+of+the+matter;+Graham+Keal+finds...-a060553497 |title=Drama that gets right to the heart of the matter; |last=Keal |first=Graham |date=8 January 1999 |work=[[Birmingham Post]] |accessdate=23 April 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17mI43C?url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/403.htm |archivedate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The series was commissioned by BBC One Controller [[Peter Salmon (producer)|Peter Salmon]], and began airing on [[BBC One]] on 12 January 1999.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/4465719.stm|title=Salmon quits as head of BBC Sport|date=21 April 2005|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060217035530/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/4465719.stm|archivedate=17 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/jan/12/tvandradio.television1 |title=Television Tuesday |last=Smithies |first=Sandy |date=12 January 1999 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=14 February 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17jXUmJ?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/1999/jan/12/tvandradio.television1 |archivedate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nSeries producer [[Richard Stokes]] believes that the series' popularity stems from the fact the hospital setting presents numerous plotline opportunities, explaining: \"You have licence to create life-and-death situations every week, something you cannot do in any other set piece. The interaction of the characters can be sexy and social issues also permeate the writing. But, basically, hospital drama is successful because the viewers will forgive all the yukky bits for the wonder of a life saved.\"<ref name=\"FR\"/> The focus of the series has developed since its conception, expanding to cover extra wards, including a [[gynaecology]] ward, an [[acute assessment unit]] and a [[maternity]] ward.<ref name=\"FR\">{{cite news|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/career_and_jobs/article1140585.ece |title=Script and scalpel, please |last=Redwood |first=Fred |date=11 June 2003 |work=[[The Times]] |accessdate=5 March 2010 |location=London |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r18ALLqO?url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/career_and_jobs/article1140585.ece |archivedate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> When the maternity ward and a [[Neonatal intensive-care unit|special care baby unit]] were introduced during [[Holby City (series 4)|series four]], Young explained that new wards were necessary to allow the crew to rotate sets, maximising filming potential.<ref name=\"malyoung\">{{cite web|url=http://www.holby.tv/cgi-bin/News/fullnews.cgi?newsid1028627054,51091,|title=Holby City Hits 100|date=6 August 2002|work=Holby Gazette|accessdate=5 March 2009|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r18LrbKu?url=http://www.holby.tv/cgi-bin/News/fullnews.cgi?newsid1028627054,51091,|archivedate=6 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nEpisodes of ''Holby City'' cost around \u00a3370,000 to produce\u2014more than the BBC soap opera ''[[EastEnders]]'', at \u00a3130,000 per episode, but less than ''Casualty'' at \u00a3450,000 per episode, or ''[[Dalziel and Pascoe (TV series)|Dalziel and Pascoe]]'' at \u00a3700\u2013800,000 per episode. As ''Holby City'' is a high-volume, year-round production, it has relatively low production costs. Set-up costs can be spread over many years and standing sets can be repeatedly re-used, which is not the case for shorter series or one-off dramas.<ref>{{cite book |title=Soap opera |last=Hobson |first=Dorothy |year=2003 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |isbn= 978-0-7456-2655-0 |page=46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tzqK15wsWrIC&printsec=frontcover&q= |accessdate=5 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Holby City Hospital.jpg|thumb|right|The hospital set, at BBC Elstree Centre in Borehamwood.]]\n\nYoung remained an executive producer of ''Holby City'' until 2004, when he left the BBC to work for production company [[19 TV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/newsstory.php/4393/bbcs-mal-young-in-19tv-switch|title=BBC's Mal Young in 19TV switch|last=Taylor|first=Joanna|date=28 September 2004|work=[[The Stage]]|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611141925/http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/newsstory.php/4393/bbcs-mal-young-in-19tv-switch|archivedate=11 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Former ''Casualty'' producer [[Johnathan Young]] was an executive producer for the duration of ''Holby''{{'s}} first series, before joining [[Channel 4]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talkbackthames.tv/index.php?s=about&b=45&abc=407|title=About Us \u2013 Who's Who \u2013 Johnathan Young|publisher=[[Talkback Thames]]|accessdate=6 August 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526014844/http://www.talkbackthames.tv/index.php?s=about&b=45&abc=407|archivedate=26 May 2011}}</ref> [[Kathleen Hutchison]] served alongside Mal Young as co-executive producer from 2003 to 2004, when she left the series to become executive producer of ''EastEnders''.<ref name=\"BBCPR\">{{cite press release|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/07_july/01/holby_episode50.shtml|title=Anita Dobson, Peter Bowles and Susannah York join Holby for 50th episode|date=1 July 2003|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110118033040/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/07_july/01/holby_episode50.shtml|archivedate=18 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2004/09_september/21/berridge.shtml|title=Louise Berridge steps down as Executive Producer of EastEnders|date=21 September 2004|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025010900/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2004/09_september/21/berridge.shtml|archivedate=25 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Hutchison was succeeded by former series producer Stokes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/stokes-replaces-hutchison-on-holby/1101103.article|title=Stokes replaces Hutchison on Holby|date=4 November 2004|work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]|publisher=[[EMAP]]|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003084226/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/stokes-replaces-hutchison-on-holby/1101103.article|archivedate=3 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> who remained working on ''Holby City'' until 2006, when McHale returned to the series.<ref name=\"digital spy1\" /> McHale was the first British writer ever to become the [[showrunner]] of a major [[Peak time|prime time]] drama.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/dec/14/hoby-city-exec-producer-leave|title=Holby City exec producer to leave|last=Plunkett|first=John|date=14 December 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=30 January 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219023342/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/dec/14/hoby-city-exec-producer-leave|archivedate=19 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He resigned from the position in 2009,<ref name=\"digital spy1\" /> and was succeeded by Belinda Campbell in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/drama/holby-city/news/amanda-mealing-to-quit-holby-city/9531 |title=Amanda Mealing to quit Holby City |date=30 June 2010 |work=[[What's on TV]] |accessdate=30 June 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17PHXlL?url=http://www.whatsontv.co.uk/drama/holby-city/news/amanda-mealing-to-quit-holby-city/9531 |archivedate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> In February 2011, it was announced that Johnathan Young would return to the BBC from March, succeeding Campbell as executive producer of both ''Casualty'' and ''Holby City''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/people/talkback-drama-chief-heads-back-to-casualty/5023481.article|title=Talkback drama chief heads back to Casualty|last=Campbell|first=Lisa|date=9 February 2011|work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]|publisher=[[EMAP]]|accessdate=9 February 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004170412/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/people/talkback-drama-chief-heads-back-to-casualty/5023481.article|archivedate=4 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\n''Holby City'' storylines are planned eight months in advance.<ref name=\"DKIS\"/> The series utilises a number of scriptwriters, who are found and scheduled by script development editor Simon Harper.<ref name=\"SW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screenwritinggoldmine.com/writing-for-a-medical-show-simon-harper-holby-interview.htm|title=Screenwriting For a Medical Show \u2013 Simon Harper (Holby) Interview |work=Screenwriting Goldmine|accessdate=5 March 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415152118/http://www.screenwritinggoldmine.com/writing-for-a-medical-show-simon-harper-holby-interview.htm|archivedate=15 April 2010}}</ref> Harper receives around 20 speculative scripts a week, and also finds writers through the BBC Writers Academy, a course established in 2005 which guarantees its graduates the opportunity to work on prime time television. McHale teaches at the academy, and graduate Abi Bown went on to become a regular writer for ''Holby City''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/04_april/11/academy.shtml|title=BBC seeks next generation of tv writers for prestigious academy|date=11 April 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110062542/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2008/04_april/11/academy.shtml|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Harper also recruits writers through the BBC's Continuing Drama Shadow Scheme, open to writers from all levels of experience.<ref name=\"Shadow\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/writersroom/writing/how_we_develop_writers.shtml|title=Continuing Drama Shadow Schemes  |work=BBC Writers Room|publisher=BBC|accessdate=5 August 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110312101420/http://www.bbc.co.uk/writersroom/writing/how_we_develop_writers.shtml|archivedate=12 March 2011}}</ref> He believes that scripts which demonstrate synthesis between guest and serial storylines are \"the spine of the show\", and has stated that, \"Good, cracking, intelligent, ballsy dialogue is a must,\" explaining: \"It's about getting the characters' voices because the characters drive these shows. It is a love for and investment in these characters and the consistency of those characters.\" Harper does not require that writers are necessarily familiar with the show, and would like to attract more female scriptwriters.<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n\nMcHale wrote the series' first episode, and served as the show's lead writer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holbycity/news/a191337/holby-citys-exec-producer-stands-down.html |title='Holby City's exec producer stands down |last=Green |first=Kris |date=14 December 2009 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |publisher=[[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|Hachette Filipacchi UK]] |accessdate=30 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17Zw9V1?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/news/a191337/holby-citys-exec-producer-stands-down.html |archivedate=6 July 2010 |df= }}</ref> His 2006 promotion to executive producer was part of a bid by Controller of BBC Drama Production [[John Yorke (television producer)|John Yorke]] to \"put writers back at the heart of the process\". Yorke called McHale's promotion \"fantastic\", explaining: \"It means that for the first time you've got a writer running one of our big powerhouse BBC1 shows.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/television-drama-great-show--now-direct-it-471585.html|title=Television Drama: Great show \u2013 now direct it|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=27 March 2006|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421122937/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/television-drama-great-show--now-direct-it-471585.html|archivedate=21 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following McHale's resignation, his replacement as lead writer was Justin Young, who intends to introduce a more writer-led commissioning process from [[Holby City (series 13)|series 13]] onwards, with writers creating more of the theme and story of their episodes than was previously the case.<ref name=\"Shadow\"/>\n\n===Medical accuracy===\nTo ensure accuracy in scriptwriting, the serial employs a team of researchers to advise writers on nursing issues and health service politics.<ref name=\"FR\"/> One medical advisor was given a cameo role in the series as an orthopaedic surgeon, and another, recovery nurse Rachel Carter, appears in ''Holby City'' as a scrub nurse.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/public_sector/article642276.ece|title=Foreign ways|date=21 November 2006|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611184943/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/public_sector/article642276.ece|archivedate=11 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.borehamwoodtimes.co.uk/news/8244539.Nurse_adds_touch_of_glamour_with_Holby_City_role/|title=Barnet Hospital nurse selected as advisor on Holby City, filmed at BBC Elstree Studios|last=Drewett|first=Zoe|date=29 June 2010|work=Borehamwood Times|publisher=[[Newsquest]]|accessdate=29 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722140045/http://www.borehamwoodtimes.co.uk/news/8244539.Nurse_adds_touch_of_glamour_with_Holby_City_role/|archivedate=22 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Another adviser, a [[cardiothoracic surgery|heart surgeon]], has occasionally left [[open-heart surgery]] to advise ''Holby City'' writers over the telephone.<ref name=\"FR\"/> The programme utilises surgeons from different disciplines, who check scripts for accuracy. Carter believes this is particularly important in case viewers copy procedures they have seen in the show, such as [[Cardiopulmonary resuscitation|CPR]]. Series star [[Amanda Mealing]] commented: \"We pride ourselves on being realistic. You need to know what you are doing and why. It is a complex and foreign thing to act out an operation. For training, I watched a number of real ones.\"<ref name=\"realism\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10127811|title=Advising Holby City on getting it right|last=Lever|first=Anna-Marie|date=18 June 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=19 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919050742/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10127811|archivedate=19 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCast members are taught how to give realistic injections, monitor blood pressure and check a pulse, and some are given the opportunity to observe procedures in real hospitals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1697949.stm|title=Behind the scenes at Holby|date=25 December 2001|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721091156/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1697949.stm|archivedate=21 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Original cast member [[George Irving (English actor)|George Irving]] observed [[coronary artery bypass surgery]] performed at [[Papworth Hospital|Papworth]] and [[Middlesex Hospital]] in preparation for his role as [[Anton Meyer]], while [[Edward MacLiam]] observed [[laparoscopic surgery]] being performed before joining the cast as Greg Douglas in [[Holby City (series 12)|series twelve]].<ref>{{Cite journal|title=I'm capable of all Meyer is, but I don't have his certainty |last=Duncan|first=Andrew|date=2 October 2001|work=[[Radio Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/leisure/tv-wales/programme-news/2010/07/17/dishy-doctors-brighten-up-holby-city-55578-26866455/ |title=Dishy doctors brighten up Holby City |date=17 July 2010 |work=[[Liverpool Daily Post]] |accessdate=17 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314093801/http://www.dailypost.co.uk/leisure/tv-wales/programme-news/2010/07/17/dishy-doctors-brighten-up-holby-city-55578-26866455/ |archivedate=14 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe series uses operational [[ventilator]]s on set and these were donated to the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52250706|title=Holby gives ventilators to Nightingale hospital|date=2020-04-11|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Filming and on-screen output===\n''Holby City'' and ''Casualty'' are both set in Holby City Hospital, in the fictional county of Wyvern, in the southwest of England close to the Welsh border.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_19980913/ai_n14478986/?tag=content;col1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160108002218/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_19980913/ai_n14478986/?tag=content%3Bcol1|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 January 2016|title=Soap stars find a new role... In the Beeb's latest soap|last=Kempster|first=Doug|date=13 September 1998|work=[[Sunday Mirror]]|accessdate=12 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"setting\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/casualty/fast_facts/fast_facts_62.html |title=Casualty \u2013 Fast Facts |publisher=BBC |accessdate=17 November 2007 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17uxz3H?url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/casualty/fast_facts/fast_facts_62.html |archivedate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> The city exterior is represented by [[Bristol]], though ''Holby City'' is filmed at [[BBC Elstree Centre]] in [[Borehamwood]], Hertfordshire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/alexei-sayle-id-love-to-live-in-holby-city-ndash-nothing-like-the-real-world-666407.html |title=Alexei Sayle: I'd love to live in Holby City \u2013 nothing like the real world |last=Sayle |first=Alexei |date=21 August 2001 |work=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=5 March 2010 |archivedate=6 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17xUo5B?url=http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/alexei-sayle-id-love-to-live-in-holby-city-ndash-nothing-like-the-real-world-666407.html |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"location\"/> The ''Casualty'' set in Bristol was not large enough to encompass the surgical ward and operating theatre required for ''Holby City'', and as a result, some crossover scenes in the first episode had to be shot twice, first on the ''Casualty'' set and then again at Elstree, with cast members travelling between the two locations.<ref name=\"JT\"/> In October 2007, BBC cutbacks led ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' to report that the Elstree site would be sold, and ''Holby City'' relocated to share a set with ''Casualty'', possibly in [[Cardiff]].<ref name=\"location\">{{cite news|author=Juliette Garside |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1566816/EastEnders-evicted-in-latest-BBC-cost-cut.html |title=EastEnders evicted in latest BBC cost cut |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=21 October 2007 |accessdate=17 November 2007 |location=London |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rllGzBef?url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1566816/EastEnders-evicted-in-latest-BBC-cost-cut.html |archivedate=6 August 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> In March 2009, the BBC confirmed that ''Casualty'' would move to a new set in Cardiff, however in the following month, ''[[The Guardian]]'' announced that the BBC would retain Elstree Studios for at least another four years.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/03_march/26/casualty.shtml|title=BBC confirms Casualty move from Bristol to Cardiff area|date=26 March 2009|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110421101716/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2009/03_march/26/casualty.shtml|archivedate=21 April 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/28/eastenders-elstree-studios|title=EastEnders to stay at Elstree Studios|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=Tara|last=Conlan|date=28 April 2010|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204045903/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/28/eastenders-elstree-studios|archivedate=4 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSeveral episodes of the series have been shot on location abroad. In 2004, the romance between nurse [[Jess Griffin]] ([[Verona Joseph]]) and anaesthetist [[Zubin Khan]] ([[Art Malik]]) culminated in an episode set in Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-124417968|title=Article: I dreaded love scenes but tourists all got an Eiffel; Hospital drama beauty's fear over passion in Paris with legendary co-star Art.|last=Hendry|first=Steve|date=7 November 2004|work=[[Sunday Mail (Scotland)|Sunday Mail]]|accessdate=6 August 2010|location=Glasgow, Scotland|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following year, registrar [[Diane Lloyd]] ([[Patricia Potter]]) followed consultant [[Ric Griffin]] ([[Hugh Quarshie]]) to [[Ghana]] as part of the BBC's \"Africa lives\" series, a week of programmes bringing an exploration of African culture to UK audiences.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/03_march/15/1spring_progs.shtml|title=Africa lives on BBC ONE|date=15 March 2005|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060204234249/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/03_march/15/1spring_progs.shtml|archivedate=4 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/03_march/15/1spring.shtml|title=Africa lives on BBC ONE A week of programming brings African life into British homes|date=15 March 2005|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060214010238/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/03_march/15/1spring.shtml|archivedate=14 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2006, an episode shot in [[Switzerland]] featured consultant [[Elliot Hope]]'s ([[Paul Bradley (English actor)|Paul Bradley]]) wife Gina ([[Gillian Bevan]]) committing [[assisted suicide]] after her [[motor neurone disease]] worsened.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kitson |first1=Calli |title=10 episodes which have shaped Holby City as it airs its 1000th tonight |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/11/05/10-episodes-which-have-shaped-holby-city-as-it-airs-its-1000th-tonight-10955305/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=5 November 2019}}</ref> A 2007 episode filmed in [[Dubai]] focused on ''Holby'' registrar [[Joseph Byrne (Holby City)|Joseph Byrne]] ([[Luke Roberts (actor)|Luke Roberts]]) meeting new nurse [[Faye Morton]] ([[Patsy Kensit]]), and in 2008, Joseph and consultant [[Linden Cullen]] ([[Duncan Pow]]) travelled to [[Cape Town]] when Faye experienced difficulties there.<ref>{{cite web |title=Romance on Set for Lucky Luke |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-180408301/romance-on-set-for-lucky-luke |website=[[Liverpool Daily Post]] |publisher=([[Reach plc]] via [[Questia]]) |accessdate=8 January 2020 |date=21 June 2008}}{{subscriptionrequired}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/wk26/feature_holbycity.shtml|title=What lies beneath...|date=June 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110062542/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/proginfo/tv/wk26/feature_holbycity.shtml|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Series producer Diana Kyle stated in November 2008 that due to major BBC budget cuts, the series would not be filming abroad again for the \"foreseeable future\".<ref name=\"DKIS\">{{Cite journal| publication-date=25 November 2008 |title=Inside Soap Meets The Producers| periodical=[[Inside Soap]]}}</ref> However, on 10 December 2012, it was announced that the show had filmed one episode in [[Stockholm]], which focusses on Jac tracking down hospital CEO [[Henrik Hanssen]] ([[Guy Henry (actor)|Guy Henry]]) and exploring his backstory.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kilkelly|first1=Daniel|title='Holby City' heads to Sweden for special episode|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/holby-city/news/a444088/holby-city-heads-to-sweden-for-special-episode/|accessdate=3 January 2018|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=10 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Holby City'' is shot using the [[single-camera setup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/news/a94292/holby-team-hails-fantastic-bafta-win.html|title='Holby' team hails \"fantastic\" BAFTA win|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|date=21 April 2008|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611041648/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/news/a94292/holby-team-hails-fantastic-bafta-win.html|archivedate=11 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Filming occurs from 8am until 7pm daily, 50 weeks a year.<ref name=\"FR\"/> From July 2007 onwards, the show took on the [[filmising]] technique, giving episodes the impression of having been shot on film. Kyle stated that this was intended to attract a younger audience and modernise the programme, and that there had been a \"very positive\" response to the change.<ref name=\"DKIS\"/><ref name=\"insidesoap\">{{Cite journal | date=November 2007 |title=Ask the BOSS!| periodical=[[Inside Soap]]|page=40}}</ref> On 28 May 2010, the BBC announced that it would be launching a [[High-definition television|high definition]] (HD) simulcast of BBC One from the autumn, and that ''Holby City'' would move to HD by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/05_may/28/hd.shtml|title=BBC One HD to launch Autumn 2010|date=28 May 2010|publisher=BBC|accessdate=25 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531192128/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2010/05_may/28/hd.shtml|archivedate=31 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The series moved to HD broadcasting, with a [[BBC HD]] simulcast, from the start of series 13 in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00vj0rv|title=Shifts|publisher=[[BBC Programmes]]|accessdate=12 October 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015210244/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00vj0rv|archivedate=15 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe show's [[Holby City (series 11)|eleventh series]] saw musical montage or \"songtage\" segments become standard in each episode, introduced by McHale as a means of modernising the show. Although McHale initially considered commissioning original pieces, budgetary constraints limited choices to pre-existing tracks. The use of songtages was first popularised by the US medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', however McHale stated he was unaware of this until ''Holby City'' had already adopted the technique.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/09/television-popandrock|title=Top of the docs|last=Lawson|first=Mark|date=21 February 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=5 March 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911021225/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/feb/09/television-popandrock|archivedate=11 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Music was generally selected by each episode's scriptwriter. If the writer was not specific about which songs should be used, the producers and director would select the music in post-production. Actors also have some input: [[Hugh Quarshie]] personally selected the music he believed his character [[Ric Griffin]] would listen to in theatre.<ref name=\"DKIS\"/> Asked in June 2010 whether she felt songtages were appropriate for a serious drama show, Kyle responded: \"Yes \u2013 sometimes. On a multi-strand series such as ''Holby'', they are an excellent way of telling stories visually \u2013 a moment from each \u2013 to open or close an episode or create the passing of time in a concise way for the audience.\" Kris Green of entertainment and media website ''[[Digital Spy]]'' suggested that the number of songs used per episode could be \"very jarring\", to which Kyle replied: \"We plan to use music carefully in the future \u2013 maybe 'songtages', as above \u2013 and sourced music within a scene, that is music actually playing in the scene itself, for example on a radio \u2013 but less incidental.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/interviews/a223398/diana-kyle-series-producer-holby-city.html|title=Diana Kyle (Series Producer, 'Holby City')|last=Green|first=Kris|date=4 June 2010|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=19 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100607164203/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/interviews/a223398/diana-kyle-series-producer-holby-city.html|archivedate=7 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Broadcast===\n{{Main|List of Holby City episodes}}\n''Holby City'' premiered on 12 January 1999 on BBC One.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/jan/12/tvandradio.television1|title=Television Tuesday|last=Smithies|first=Sandy|date=12 January 1999|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=14 February 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17jXUmJ?url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/1999/jan/12/tvandradio.television1|archivedate=6 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Twenty-one series of the show have since aired, and a twenty-second began airing on 7 January 2020. The show's first series ran for nine episodes.<ref name=\"BFI\"/> In June 2000, then [[Director-General of the BBC]] [[Greg Dyke]] pledged extra funding for BBC One, some of which was used for extra episodes of ''Holby City''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/799874.stm|title=Dyke pledges cash for 'failing' BBC|date=22 June 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110062542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/799874.stm|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The second and third series ran for 16 and 30 episodes respectively, with new episodes then airing on a weekly basis from the fourth series onwards.<ref name=\"BFI\"/> Series four to nine and eleven all ran for 52 episodes, while series ten ran for 53 episodes, including the stand-alone finale episode \"Mad World\", set outside the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv-entertainment/tv/todays-tv/2008/10/14/we-love-drama-holby-city-115875-20802412/|title=We love drama: Holby City|last=Simon|first=Jane|date=14 October 2008|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=12 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719093030/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv-entertainment/tv/todays-tv/2008/10/14/we-love-drama-holby-city-115875-20802412/|archivedate=19 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> All series from then on continued to consist of 52 episodes, with exception to the twelfth series, which consisted of 55 episodes in total. Young explained of the increase in series length: \"Longer runs allow you to develop really strong storylines for the regular characters. As long as you do volume with passion, it'll work.\"<ref name=\"malyoung\" /> The series reached its 500th episode on 13 April 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/12/holby-city-celebrates-500-episodes|title=Holby City celebrates 500 episodes but TV mourns the passing of The Bill|last=Armstrong|first=Stephen|date=12 April 2010|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=20 April 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140724022428/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/12/holby-city-celebrates-500-episodes|archivedate=24 July 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThroughout ''Holby City''{{'s}} first series, episodes were 50 minutes long. From the second series onwards, episodes have been one hour in length.<ref name=\"BFI\">{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/series/30842|title=Holby City|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=20 April 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018191638/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/series/30842|archivedate=18 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The show was originally broadcast on Tuesday nights at 8.10&nbsp;pm, until a switch to Thursdays occurred for the second series, which began broadcasting in November 1999.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Halfway through the third series in 2001, Holby reverted to its original Tuesday night slot, but now at 8.05&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Keri+wards+off+Sophie+trouble;+Holby+City+BBC1,+8.05pm.-a069882478|title=Keri wards off Sophie trouble; Holby City BBC1, 8.05&nbsp;pm|date=3 February 2001|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|accessdate=4 April 2010|location=Glasgow, Scotland|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130204015057/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Keri+wards+off+Sophie+trouble;+Holby+City+BBC1,+8.05pm.-a069882478|archivedate=4 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Finally, the show moved into the 8pm timeslot, where it has since remained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/George+gets+to+heart+of+the+matter;+TELLY.-a078992867|title=George gets to heart of the matter|date=9 October 2001|work=[[Liverpool Echo]]|accessdate=10 October 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120914150301/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/George+gets+to+heart+of+the+matter;+TELLY.-a078992867|archivedate=14 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The show is occasionally broadcast on a different day dependent on BBC scheduling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/dec/15/overnights|title=Extinct's audience under threat|last=Tryhorn|first=Chris|date=15 December 2006|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=14 February 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140928215358/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/dec/15/overnights|archivedate=28 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2007, the show temporarily moved to Thursday nights, allowing ''HolbyBlue'' to air in the 8pm Tuesday timeslot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/may/18/overnights|title=Emmerdale eclipses EastEnders|last=Tryhorn|first=Chris|date=18 May 2007|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=14 February 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003124926/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/may/18/overnights|archivedate=3 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  [[BBC One Scotland]] has for the most part broadcast the series at a later time (mainly at 10.40pm), with its slot at 8pm filled by [[River City]].\n\nIn February 2019, it was announced that repeats of ''Holby City'' would begin airing on the channel [[Drama (UK TV channel)|Drama]], starting from the first series of the drama.<ref>{{cite web |title=Classic Holby City |url=https://drama.uktv.co.uk/shows/holby-city/ |publisher=[[Drama (UK TV channel)|Drama]] |accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe show airs in [[Finland]] on the channel [[Yle TV2]] under the name of \"Holby Cityn sairaala\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Holby Cityn sairaala |url=https://areena.yle.fi/1-2185328 |website=areena.yle.fi |accessdate=31 March 2019 |language=fi}}</ref>\n\n==Characters and cast==\n\n===Characters===\n{{Main|Characters of Holby City}}\n{{See also|List of Holby City characters}}\n\n''Holby City'' follows the professional and personal lives of medical and ancillary staff at Holby General. It features an ensemble cast of main and recurring characters. New main characters have been both written in and out of the series regularly since it started, the show contains a core of 10 to 20 main characters on the show at any given time.<ref name=\"FR\"/>\n\nThe original cast of 11 characters featured in the show's first episode consisted of [[Consultant (medicine)|consultants]] [[Anton Meyer]] ([[George Irving (English actor)|George Irving]]) and Muriel McKendrick ([[Phyllis Logan]]), [[Specialist registrar|registrars]] [[Nick Jordan (character)|Nick Jordan]] ([[Michael French]]) and Kirstie Collins ([[Dawn McDaniel]]), [[senior house officer]] Victoria Merrick ([[Lisa Faulkner]]), [[Staff nurse|ward sister]] Karen Newburn ([[Sarah Preston]]), theatre sister Ellie Sharpe (Julie Saunders), senior staff nurse Ray Sykes ([[Ian Curtis (actor)|Ian Curtis]]), staff nurses Julie Bradford ([[Nicola Stephenson]]) and Jasmine Hopkins ([[Angela Griffin]]), and ward clerk Paul Ripley ([[Luke Mably]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/612924?view=cast|title=Cast \u2013 Holby City: Happy Families|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021061921/http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/612924?view=cast|archivedate=21 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, the series features an ensemble of main characters consultant neurosurgeon and acting chief executive officer Max McGerry ([[Jo Martin]]), consultant general surgeon and medical director [[Ric Griffin]] ([[Hugh Quarshie]]), consultant cardiothoracic surgeon and co-clinical lead - Darwin [[Jac Naylor]] ([[Rosie Marcel]]), consultant cardiothoracic surgeon and co-clinical lead - Darwin Kian Madani ([[Ramin Karimloo]]), consultant general surgeon and Clinical Lead - AAU [[Ange Godard]] ([[Dawn Steele]]), consultant general surgeon and Clinical Lead - Keller [[Sacha Levy]] ([[Bob Barrett (actor)|Bob Barrett]]), consultant general surgeon Ben Sherwood ([[Charlie Condou]]), speciality registrars [[Dominic Copeland]] ([[David Ames (actor)|David Ames]]), [[Xavier Duval]] (Marcus Griffiths), and Chloe Godard ([[Amy Lennox]]), foundation training doctors [[Nicky McKendrick]] ([[Belinda Owusu]]) and Cameron Dunn (Nic Jackman), director of nursing [[Adrian Fletcher (character)|Adrian \"Fletch\" Fletcher]] ([[Alex Walkinshaw]]), and senior staff nurses [[Donna Jackson]] ([[Jaye Jacobs]]) and [[Essie Harrison]] ([[Kaye Wragg]]).\n\n===Casting===\nIn casting the [[Holby City (series 1)|first series]] of ''Holby City'', Young\u2014who had previously worked on the soap operas ''[[Brookside]]'' and ''[[Family Affairs]]''\u2014selected actors who were already established names in the acting industry, particularly from a soap opera background.<ref name=\"GK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Drama+that+gets+right+to+the+heart+of+the+matter;+Graham+Keal+finds...-a060553497|title=Drama that gets right to the heart of the matter;|last=Keal|first=Graham|date=8 January 1999|work=[[Birmingham Post]]|accessdate=23 April 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5r17mI43C?url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/403.htm|archivedate=6 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> French had starred in the BBC's ''EastEnders'', while Stephenson and Faulkner had starred in ''Brookside''.<ref name=\"JT\"/> Griffin had also appeared in [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s ''[[Coronation Street]]''.<ref name=\"GK\"/> Young explained: \"Some of the best performances on screen have come out of soaps in the past few years. There is a fantastic amount of talent on those shows.\"<ref name=\"JT\"/> This propensity for hiring established actors continued as the soap progressed, with former ''[[Brookside]]'' actress [[Patricia Potter]] cast as registrar [[Diane Lloyd]], ''[[Star Wars]]'' actor [[Denis Lawson]] cast as consultant [[Tom Campbell-Gore]], and ''[[Family Affairs]]'' star [[Rocky Marshall]] cast as SHO [[Ed Keating]].<ref name=\"malyoung\"/> Later roles were awarded to comedian [[Adrian Edmondson]], former film actress [[Patsy Kensit]], and ''[[Jesus of Nazareth (miniseries)|Jesus of Nazareth]]'' star Powell.<ref name=\"shelley\">{{cite news|author=Jim Shelley|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2007/oct/03/tvdinnershowtomakeabbcm|title=How to make a BBC medical drama|date=3 October 2007|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 October 2007|location=London|authorlink=Jim Shelley (TV critic)|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219025052/http://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2007/oct/03/tvdinnershowtomakeabbcm|archivedate=19 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> When [[Jane Asher]] was cast in the recurring role of [[Lady Byrne]] in 2007, ''[[Inside Soap]]'' magazine asked Kyle whether the production team intentionally sought out \"well-known-names\". She responded: \"It's lovely when we have a new member of the cast come in and bring an audience with them. But we want the best actors, and the star names we cast are always the best \u2013 which is why we go for them.\"<ref name=\"insidesoap\"/>\n\nThere is a casting department at Elstree Studios which casts actors for ''Holby City'' as well as ''Casualty'', ''EastEnders'' and ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''. The programme also has two dedicated casting directors who bring in a shortlist of actors for the producer and director to audition.<ref name=\"DKIS\"/> Some cast members who play main characters have made previous appearances in ''Holby City'' in minor roles. Mealing appeared as the mother of a paediatric patient in the show's [[Holby City (series 4)|fourth series]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=Shadow of a Doubt, Part I|episodelink=Holby City (series 4)|series=Holby City|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC One]]|airdate=31 December 2001|season=4|number=13|credits=[[Keith Boak]] (director), Neil McKay (writer)}}</ref> Roberts appeared as the son of a medical professor in ''Holby City''{{'s}} [[Holby City (series 7)|seventh series]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=No Pain, No Gain|episodelink=Holby City (series 7)|series=Holby City|network=[[BBC]]|station=[[BBC One]]|airdate=10 May 2005|season=7|number=30|credits=[[Alice Troughton]] (director), John Milne (writer)}}</ref> and Dhillon appeared as anaesthetist Sunil Gupta in 2001.<ref name=\"tpa2\">{{cite news|title=Familiar face at Holby|work=[[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|Metro]]|date=31 October 2007|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/73760-familiar-face-at-holby|accessdate=27 February 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929133506/http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/73760-familiar-face-at-holby|archivedate=29 September 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Roberts believes that his single scene in series seven was enough for him to be called in for the part of Joseph,<ref name=\"croydon\">{{cite news|title=Luke Roberts Interview|publisher=icCroydon|date=January 2006}}</ref> while in contrast, Dhillon does not believe that his role contributed to his casting as Michael, but instead worried that it would work against him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holby.tv/cgi-bin/News/fullnews.cgi?newsid1225154017,34428, |title=Hari Dhillon Interview |work=Holby Gazette |date=28 October 2008 |accessdate=22 June 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===Guest stars===\n''Holby City'' has featured a number of famous guest stars. [[Emma Samms]], [[Antonio Fargas]], [[Ronald Pickup]] and [[Leslie Phillips]] made appearances within the show's first few series, and [[Anita Dobson]], [[Peter Bowles]] and [[Susannah York]] all appeared in the fiftieth episode.<ref name=\"BBCPR\"/> Other notable guest stars include [[Paul Blackthorne]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/2137986.stm|title=Famous Fan: Paul Blackthorne|date=19 July 2002|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113013816/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/2137986.stm|archivedate=13 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Suzanne Shaw]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1150374.stm|title=Celebrations for winning Popstars|date=4 February 2001|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527145226/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1150374.stm|archivedate=27 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Geoffrey Hutchings]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10494592|title=Stage and TV actor Geoffrey Hutchings dies aged 71|date=2 July 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720102602/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10494592|archivedate=20 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Richard Todd]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8394977.stm|title=Obituary: Richard Todd|date=4 December 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091210062242/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8394977.stm|archivedate=10 December 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Johnny Briggs (actor)|Johnny Briggs]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6251333.stm|title=Charles back on Coronation Street|date=11 January 2007|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926074334/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6251333.stm|archivedate=26 September 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Terence Rigby]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7554044.stm|title=Actor Terence Rigby dies aged 71|date=11 August 2008|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413235822/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7554044.stm|archivedate=13 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Michael Obiora]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8136063.stm|title=Hotel Babylon star on coeliac disease|last=Briggs|first=Helen|date=9 July 2009|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010}}</ref> and [[Lionel Jeffries]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3717820.stm|title=Obituary: Lionel Jeffries|date=19 February 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026101813/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3717820.stm|archivedate=26 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Richard Briers]] appeared as patient George Woodman in the Christmas episode \"Elliot's Wonderful Life\", [[Eric Sykes]] played Roger Ludlow, a patient with [[Alzheimer's disease]] and [[Phill Jupitus]] starred as morbidly obese patient Andy Thompson. [[Kieron Dyer]] was in four episodes as an injury prone footballer, [[Denise Welch]] had a recurring role as risk manager Pam McGrath, mother of nurse [[Keri McGrath|Keri]], [[Clarke Peters]] appeared for five episodes in 2009 as the father of nurse Donna Jackson, and [[Graeme Garden]] had a recurring role from 2003 to 2007 as cardiothoracic consultant Edward Loftwood. [[Cascade Brown]] played Sophie Hindmarsh in 2004, [[Antonio Fargas]] appeared in 2003 as Victor Garrison, a patient with [[Parkinson's disease]], [[Sheridan Smith]] appeared for six episodes in 2001 as teenage stalker Miranda Locke, and [[David Soul]] made two appearances as Professor Alan Fletcher.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} The BBC's William Gallagher wrote in a November 2001 column that Soul's guest-appearance had begun a trend for American actors appearing in UK shows.<ref name=\"WG\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1631573.stm|title=This week's TV: All Change|last=Gallagher|first=William|date=1 November 2001|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524214832/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1631573.stm|archivedate=24 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2012, [[Ron Moody]] guest starred as patient Vincent Mancini, a war veteran.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/news/a387553/holby-city-role-for-fagin-actor-ron-moody.html#~pdDs3OKrqbuOsH|title='Holby City' role for Fagin actor Ron Moody|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=15 June 2012|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=24 May 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615082029/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s19/holby-city/news/a387553/holby-city-role-for-fagin-actor-ron-moody.html#~pdDs3OKrqbuOsH|archivedate=15 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the BBC reached an agreement with the actors' union [[Equity (trade union)|Equity]] to cease offering walk-on drama series roles to members of the public as prizes. When an untrained person won such a role in ''Holby City'' in a competition, Equity complained to the broadcaster that such prizes were \"demeaning\" to actors, depriving them of paid employment. The competition winner was allowed to visit the ''Holby City'' set, but did not appear on-screen as a result of the policy change.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3041446.stm|title=BBC ends public 'walk-on' roles|date=3 July 2003|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Adaptations and other appearances==\n\n===''Casualty@Holby City''===\n{{Main|Casualty@Holby City}}\nReflecting ''Holby City''{{'s}} origins as a spin-off from ''Casualty'' and the closely related premises of the two programmes, the BBC has screened occasional crossover mini-dramas entitled ''Casualty@Holby City'', featuring a number of characters from each of the two casts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/apr/27/broadcasting.bbc|title=Holby City walks the thin blue line|last=Plunkett|first=John|date=27 April 2006|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 January 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204122047/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/apr/27/broadcasting.bbc|archivedate=4 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Prior to the commissioning of ''Casualty@Holby City'', the two shows had occasionally crossed-over storylines and cast members before; for instance developing a romance between ''Holby City''{{'s}} [[Ben Saunders (Holby City)|Ben Saunders]] ([[David Paisley]]) and ''Casualty''{{'s}} Tony Vincent ([[Lee Warburton]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2985375.stm|title=Virgin Mary complaints rejected|date=29 April 2003|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111018185502/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2985375.stm|archivedate=18 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The first full crossover was spearheaded by ''Casualty''{{'s}} executive producer Mervyn Watson, and ''Holby City''{{'s}} McHale. Logistical difficulties arose from the fact the two series are usually produced 120 miles apart, and work on both shows had to be halted for two weeks to release a number of cast members to appear in the special.<ref name=\"watson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/casualty/christmas2004/interview/|title=Crossover Interview|publisher=BBC|date=December 2004|accessdate=14 September 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110025712/http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/casualty/christmas2004/interview/|archivedate=10 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nA second crossover was commissioned in 2005 as part of the BBC's DoNation season, aiming to raise public awareness of [[organ donation]] and help viewers make an informed decision about whether to sign up to the Organ Donor Register. An interactive episode of ''Casualty@Holby City'' was one of the headlining shows of the season, allowing viewers to vote by phone to determine the outcome of a fictional organ donation.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite pressrelease|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/04_april/28/donation.shtml|title=Major BBC organ donation season launches in August|publisher=BBC|date=28 April 2005|accessdate=20 April 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110030015/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/04_april/28/donation.shtml|archivedate=10 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The third ''Casualty@Holby City'' crossover aired in October 2005. The four-part storyline tackled the issue of youth violence, following the events of a turbulent A&E demonstration at an inner-city school.<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news|url=http://media.guardian.co.uk/bbc/story/0,,1571141,00.html|title=Casualty and Holby reunited for youth violence special|first=Tara|last=Conlan|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=16 September 2005|accessdate=20 April 2010}}</ref> Based on the success of the 2004 ''Casualty@Holby City'' Christmas special, another crossover was ordered for Christmas 2005. Rather than dividing the episodes between the two series' crews as had previously been standard, this crossover operated as an entirely separate production, with Kyle producing and Paul Harrison directing.<ref name=\"watson2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/casualty/christmas2005/interview/|title=Crossover Interview|publisher=BBC|date=December 2005|accessdate=20 April 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110030023/http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/casualty/christmas2005/interview/|archivedate=10 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, another crossover occurred when ''Casualty''{{'s}} [[Charlie Fairhead]] ([[Derek Thompson (actor)|Derek Thompson]]) was operated on by ''Holby City''{{'s}} Elliot Hope after suffering a heart attack. The storyline was, however, broadcast as regular ''Casualty'' and ''Holby City'' episodes, rather than under the ''Casualty@Holby City'' title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00qy03r|title=Casualty, Series 24, Love Is a Battlefield|publisher=BBC|accessdate=20 April 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210225432/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00qy03r|archivedate=10 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00qxzqn|title=Holby City, Series 12, Downstairs Upstairs|publisher=BBC|accessdate=20 April 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100219101923/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00qxzqn|archivedate=19 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Casualty''{{'s}} series producer Oliver Kent commented that, while it is \"fantastic\" to be able to produce crossover episodes, they are logistically difficult,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s18/casualty/news/a158194/casualty-holby-city-crossover-planned.html|title='Casualty', 'Holby City' crossover planned|last=Green|first=Kris|date=5 June 2009|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=4 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211154145/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s18/casualty/news/a158194/casualty-holby-city-crossover-planned.html|archivedate=11 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and it is unlikely that another ''Casualty@Holby City'' episode will be produced in the \"foreseeable future\". In September 2010, ''Holby City''{{'s}} nurse [[Donna Jackson]] ([[Jaye Jacobs]]) appeared in ''Casualty'', and Kent hopes that characters from the two shows will begin to crossover two or three times a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s18/casualty/news/a228848/casualty-plans-more-holby-crossovers.html|title='Casualty' plans more 'Holby' crossovers|last=Kilkelly|first=Daniel|date=17 June 2010|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=25 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620234811/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s18/casualty/news/a228848/casualty-plans-more-holby-crossovers.html|archivedate=20 June 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===HolbyBlue===\n{{Main|HolbyBlue}}\nOn 27 April 2006, the BBC announced the commissioning of ''Holby Blue'', a police procedural spin-off from ''Holby City'' created by [[Tony Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/apr/27/broadcasting.bbc|title=Holby City walks the thin blue line|last=Plunkett|first=John|date=27 April 2006|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204122047/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2006/apr/27/broadcasting.bbc|archivedate=4 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jordan contemplated that \"soap snobs\" may hold the series in disdain for using the ''Holby'' brand, but concluded: \"After much thought, I remembered who I was as a writer, the joy I take from surprising an audience, by subverting expectation \u2013 and ''HolbyBlue'' was born.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/may/08/tvandradio.bbc|title=Stop thief \u2013 or I'll fill out a form!|last=Jordan|first=Tony|authorlink=Tony Jordan|date=8 May 2007|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=13 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141003124556/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/may/08/tvandradio.bbc|archivedate=3 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Holby City'' was moved to Thursdays for the duration of ''HolbyBlue''{{'s}} first series, with the spin-off broadcast on Tuesday nights at 8&nbsp;pm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.thestage.co.uk/tvtoday/2007/07/the-false-economy-of-holby-blue/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319150529/http://blogs.thestage.co.uk/tvtoday/2007/07/the-false-economy-of-holby-blue/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 March 2012 |title=The False Economy of Holby Blue |last=Wright |first=Mark |date=5 July 2007 |work=[[The Stage]] |accessdate=12 July 2010 }}</ref> A two-part crossover episode with ''Holby City'' was developed for the beginning of the show's second series, broadcast in 2008. The episodes were written by McHale and Jordan, and saw ''Holby City'' registrar Jac Naylor accused of murder.<ref>{{cite news|author=Kris Green|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s40/holby-blue/news/a79838/holbyblue-returns-with-crossover-ep.html|title='HolbyBlue' returns with crossover ep|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=14 November 2007|accessdate=18 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610212810/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/s40/holby-blue/news/a79838/holbyblue-returns-with-crossover-ep.html|archivedate=10 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Yorke compared the crossover to the American [[CSI (franchise)|''CSI'' franchise]], in that: \"You really believe it's a world.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Matthew|last=Hemley|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/newsstory.php/18854/tony-jordan-returns-to-write-for-eastenders|title=Tony Jordan returns to write for EastEnders|work=[[The Stage]]|date=14 November 2007|accessdate=18 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611222353/http://www.thestage.co.uk/news/newsstory.php/18854/tony-jordan-returns-to-write-for-eastenders|archivedate=11 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> While the second series attracted 5.6&nbsp;million viewers with its opening episode, by the end of May 2008 viewership had fallen to 2.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|title= BBC axes police drama Holby Blue|publisher= BBC News|date= 6 August 2008|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7545311.stm|accessdate=6 August 2008}}</ref> In August 2008, the BBC announced that due to declining ratings, ''Holby Blue'' would not be recommissioned for a third series.<ref>{{cite news|last= Welsh|first= James|title= BBC takes axe to 'Holby Blue'|work= [[Digital Spy]]|date= 6 August 2008|url= http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/broadcasting/a119807/bbc-takes-axe-to-holby-blue.html|accessdate= 6 August 2008|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080808075757/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/broadcasting/a119807/bbc-takes-axe-to-holby-blue.html|archivedate= 8 August 2008|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Other appearances===\nIn June 2002, cast members from ''Holby City'' and ''Casualty'' competed against the ''EastEnders'' cast for the first ''[[Sport Relief]]'' fundraiser, in a segment dubbed \"Sport in the Square\". The teams competed in events such as taxi pulling, melon tossing and a beer keg relay.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/special_events/sport_relief/2126921.stm|title=Sport Relief as it happened|date=13 July 2002|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103022540/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/special_events/sport_relief/2126921.stm|archivedate=3 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The competition was televised on BBC One, and the event as a whole raised \u00a310&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2127609.stm|title=Sports Relief raises \u00a310m|date=14 July 2002|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202201057/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2127609.stm|archivedate=2 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2003, BBC One aired a \"Kenyon Confronts\" documentary by ''[[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]]'' reporter Paul Kenyon, investigating hospitals run by the [[Private Finance Initiative]]. He discovered many problems within the hospitals, which were dramatised by the ''Holby City'' cast in specially commissioned scenes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article1167339.ece|title=Viewing Guide|last=Chater|first=David|date=8 October 2003|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615055545/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article1167339.ece|archivedate=15 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> March 2004 saw the station air the documentary \"Making It at Holby\", as part of a BBC initiative to develop new acting talent. The documentary followed the casting process of ''Holby City'' and ''Casualty'', from the audition stages to the filming of the selected actors' first scenes. Young explained his casting criteria, stating: \"I try to put my head into the head of a viewer and ask: do I want to spend three years in the life of this person?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article1050337.ece|title=Viewing Guide|last=Chater|first=David|date=23 March 2003|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615055644/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article1050337.ece|archivedate=15 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe 17 November 2006 ''[[Children in Need]]'' charity [[telethon]] included a segment featuring the ''Holby City'' cast performing a comical version of \"[[Hung Up]]\" by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].<ref name=\"childreninneed\">{{cite news|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/25664-stars-line-up-for-children-in-need|title=Stars line up for Children in Need|work=[[Metro (Associated Metro Limited)|Metro]]|date=17 November 2006|accessdate=31 August 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522101731/http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/25664-stars-line-up-for-children-in-need|archivedate=22 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The 16 November 2007 ''[[Children in Need]]'' appeal again contained a musical performance from Holby City cast members. [[Sharon D Clarke]], backed by [[Nadine Lewington]], [[Rakie Ayola]] and [[Phoebe Thomas]] performed a soul version of [[Aretha Franklin]]'s signature song, \"[[Respect (song)|Respect]]\".<ref name=\"childreninneed07\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/11_november/17/cin.shtml|title=Record-breaking \u00a319m raised by BBC Children in Need so far...|publisher=BBC|date=17 November 2007|accessdate=17 November 2007|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005134030/http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/11_november/17/cin.shtml|archivedate=5 October 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode |title=Children in Need 2007 |episodelink=Children in Need 2007 |series=Children in Need |serieslink=Children in Need |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC One]] |airdate=16 November 2007}}</ref> On 28 June 2008, ''Holby City'' stars competed against their ''Casualty'' counterparts in a special charity edition of [[BBC Two]] game-show ''[[The Weakest Link]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00cfmz1|title=Holby City and Casualty Special|publisher=BBC|accessdate=4 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113070845/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00cfmz1|archivedate=13 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Holby City'' and ''Casualty'' cast members united on 20 February 2010, performing a dance rendition of \"[[Jai Ho (song)|Jai Ho]]\" for ''[[Let's Dance for Sport Relief]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a204535/hound-brand-make-lets-dance-final.html|title=Hound, Brand make 'Let's Dance' final|last=Fletcher|first=Alex|date=22 February 2010|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=4 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100225154703/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a204535/hound-brand-make-lets-dance-final.html|archivedate=25 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n[[File:Holby City map.jpg|thumb|left|A map of the hospital's internal layout]]\n\n===Critical response===\n''Holby City'' has attracted comparisons to other medical dramas, often unfavourable. In November 2002, John Whiston, then head of drama at [[Granada Television#Takeover bids|Granada Television]], accused the BBC of producing \"ersatz parodies\" of ITV drama, commenting that: \"With ''Holby City'' cloned out of ''Casualty'', the BBC has even ended up copying itself.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article828295.ece|title=ITV win Miss Marple in ratings battle|last=Snoddy|first=Raymond|date=13 November 2003|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001159/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article828295.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Paul Hoggart of ''[[The Times]]'' has written that the differences between the two shows are \"mild\", calling ''Holby City'': \"''Casualty''{{'s}} cute little sister\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article871323.ece|title=Paul Hoggart: Television|last=Hoggart|first=Paul|date=3 May 2003|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615055016/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article871323.ece|archivedate=15 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Kevin Lygo]], director of television at Channel 4, referred to ''Holby City'' as \"sudsy drama\", deeming it, ''Casualty'' and ''HolbyBlue'' \"all decent programmes, but strikingly similar in many aspects of their tone and construction.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/kevin-lygo-on-broadcasting-446768.html|title=Kevin Lygo on Broadcasting|first=Kevin|last=Lygo|authorlink=Kevin Lygo|work=[[The Independent]]|date=30 April 2007|accessdate=7 August 2010|location=London}}</ref> ''Holby City'' has also been unfavourably compared with the American medical drama ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''. Television producer [[Paul Abbott]] has commented that although he watches ''ER'', he does not watch ''Holby City'' as: \"it looks like you've crammed one hour's drama into 26 episodes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/shame-on-the-lot-of-you-paul-abbott-on-the-betrayal-of-tv-drama-422152.html|title=Shame on the lot of you: Paul Abbott on the betrayal of TV drama|last=Burrell|first=Ian|date=30 October 2006|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325091822/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/shame-on-the-lot-of-you-paul-abbott-on-the-betrayal-of-tv-drama-422152.html|archivedate=25 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2009, former ''Holby City'' writer [[Peter Jukes]] wrote a critical piece for ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'' magazine, contrasting the show negatively with the standard of American television dramas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/organgrinder/2009/oct/29/the-wire-us-television|title=They get The Wire, we get Casualty|last=Lusher|first=Tim|date=29 October 2009|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=30 January 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205003502/http://www.theguardian.com/media/organgrinder/2009/oct/29/the-wire-us-television|archivedate=5 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Jukes wrote that ''Holby City'' has become a soap opera, rather than a drama, and deemed the episodes he worked on \"the most dispiriting experiences in [his] 25 years as a dramatist.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/2009/10/why-britain-cant-do-the-wire/|title=Why Britain can't do The Wire|last=Jukes|first=Peter|date=21 October 2009|work=[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]|accessdate=30 January 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811061400/http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/2009/10/why-britain-cant-do-the-wire/|archivedate=11 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn several occasions, people within the television and entertainment industry have suggested that ''Holby City'' is a waste of the television [[licence fee]], with some suggesting that it ought to be cancelled. In August 2002, Paul Bolt, director of the [[Broadcasting Standards Commission]] criticised BBC programming as being \"humdrum\" and \"formulaic\", saying of ''Holby City'' and the police procedural ''[[Mersey Beat]]'': \"One begins to wonder what really is the point of the BBC bringing this to us. Let's have something a bit different.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2194979.stm|title=TV watchdog raps 'humdrum' BBC|publisher=BBC News|date=15 August 2002|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228015922/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2194979.stm|archivedate=28 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Then head of BBC drama [[Jane Tranter]] responded that Bolt's examples were \"highly selective\" as well as \"hugely patronising to the millions of viewers who enjoy popular dramas like ''Holby City'' \u2013 week in, week out\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2198497.stm|title=BBC hits back at 'humdrum' tag|publisher=BBC News|date=16 August 2002|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110062542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2198497.stm|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Young, who at the time held the position of head of drama serials, told ''The Guardian'': \"Popular drama has always been singled out for criticism, but people are increasingly voting with their on-buttons.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2207205.stm|title=Slanging match over BBC output|first=Torin|last=Douglas|publisher=BBC News|date=21 August 2002|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110062542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2207205.stm|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Also in 2002, David Cox of the ''[[New Statesman]]'' criticised BBC One's 2001 Christmas schedule, for airing ''Holby City'' against a contemporary version of ''[[Othello]]''. On this basis, Cox advocated the abolition of the licence fee, explaining: \"The BBC was invented in a period when the elite decided what the population should know. If that has gone, then the licence fee should go too.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article820633.ece?token=null&offset=24&page=3|title=Focus: Could this man zap the BBC for \u00a32.5 billion?|last=Hellen|first=Nicholas|date=3 November 2002|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=4 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605000246/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article820633.ece?token=null&offset=24&page=3|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the 2003 [[Edinburgh International Television Festival]], BSykB chief executive [[Tony Ball]] called for stricter restrictions on how the BBC spent licence payers' money, suggesting that ''Holby City'' be sold to the channel's commercial rivals, with the proceeds used to develop more original programming.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3182191.stm|title=Hot debate over BBC future|first=Nick|last=Higham|publisher=BBC News|date=26 August 2003|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110062542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3182191.stm|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3120894.stm|title=BBC under media moguls' scrutiny|first=Torin|last=Douglas|publisher=BBC News|date=18 September 2003|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110062542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3120894.stm|archivedate=10 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The BBC refused Ball's suggestion, responding in a statement: \"This speech clearly reflects BSkyB's view that programmes are merely a commodity to be bought and sold.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3173269.stm|title=BBC should 'sell off shows'|publisher=BBC News|date=23 August 2003|accessdate=3 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105131720/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3173269.stm|archivedate=5 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In June 2004, [[Charles Allen (businessman)|Charles Allen]], chief executive of [[ITV plc]] questioned the amount of funding spent on lengthened episodes of ''Holby City'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3791493.stm|title=ITV boss in ratings appeal to BBC|date=9 June 2004|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040722033435/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3791493.stm|archivedate=22 July 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and in January 2010, [[Janet Street-Porter]] of ''[[The Independent]]'', opined ''Holby City'' had \"come to the end of [its] natural life\" and should be cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/janet-street-porter/editoratlarge-a-999-call-is-a-call-for-help-pity-the-police-dont-know-1884348.html|title=Editor-At-Large: A 999 call is a call for help. Pity the police don't know|last=Street-Porter|first=Janet|date=31 January 2010|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=1 February 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100202112750/http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/janet-street-porter/editoratlarge-a-999-call-is-a-call-for-help-pity-the-police-dont-know-1884348.html|archivedate=2 February 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Holby City'' was praised by campaigners for the [[Royal National Institute for Deaf People]] (RNID) in October 2003, when an episode which coincided with \"Learn To Sign Week\" used deaf actors, and featured characters communicating through [[British Sign Language]]. RNID chief executive John Low stated: \"Too often individuals have to rely on family members or friends to communicate complicated personal information to professionals. This is the reason the RNID is calling on the government to channel funding into the training of British Sign Language interpreters who could then be available to NHS staff treating deaf patients.\" Stokes commented: \"The writer had a great story he wanted to tell \u2013 for us, that's what matters first and foremost.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3180550.stm|title=Holby signs way forward|last=Adams-Spink|first=Geoff|date=13 October 2003|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060223122200/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3180550.stm|archivedate=23 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A 2008 report into ethnic diversity on television, commissioned by Channel 4, cited ''Holby City'' as a positive example of \"diverse British programm[ing]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7511439.stm|title=TV soaps 'stereotype minorities'|date=17 July 2008|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090310163900/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7511439.stm|archivedate=10 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Five years previously in 2003, former BBC host [[Sir Ludovic Kennedy]] complained that ethnic minorities were over-represented on television, prompting a BBC spokeswoman to explain that ''Holby City'' has more ethnic characters as it is set in an area where minorities account for up to 30% of the population.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3142568.stm|title=Row over black TV stars|date=26 September 2003|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030928043040/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3142568.stm|archivedate=28 September 2003|df=dmy-all}}</ref> According to the 2001 census, the population of Bristol \u2013 which the city of Holby is loosely based upon \u2013 is 88% white and 12% ethnic minorities.\n\n===Realism===\nThe show has been criticised for its lack of realism. Former nurse Vici Hoban commented in February 2004 that there existed three stereotypes with regards to nurses: \"sex object, doctor's handmaiden, or angel\". She felt that media portrayal had increased these misconceptions, observing that with \"the syringe-toting serial killer [[Kelly Yorke|Kelly]] in ''Holby City'', realism has never been top of TV's agenda.\" However, Hoban felt that the worst offender at the time was the Channel 4 medical drama ''[[No Angels (TV series)|No Angels]]'', which she described as: \"so inaccurate that it makes ''Holby City'' look like a factual documentary.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article1027700.ece|title=Reality check-up|last=Hoban|first=Vici|date=28 February 2008|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615055800/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article1027700.ece|archivedate=15 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''No Angels'' creator [[Toby Whithouse]] defended his series, stating that ''Holby City'' presents an unfair representation of nursing, deceiving viewers into believing that nursing \"is a nice, clean job full of handsome doctors.\" Whithouse observed that the content of ''Holby City'' is defined by the [[Watershed (broadcasting)|watershed]], describing real nursing work in contrast as \"very post-watershed\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/angels-with-dirty-faces-570181.html|title=Angels with dirty faces |last=Gilbert|first=Gerard|date=16 February 2002|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=5 March 2010 | location=London}}</ref> In November 2009, Antony Sumara, CEO of the Mid Staffordshire NHS Foundation Hospital Trust, wrote a column criticising ''Holby City'' for misrepresenting real hospital life.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8363860.stm|title=TV dramas 'misrepresent the NHS'|last=Sumara|first=Antony|date=18 November 2009|publisher=BBC|accessdate=23 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121104717/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8363860.stm|archivedate=21 November 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Tom Sutcliffe (broadcaster)|Tom Sutcliffe]] of ''[[The Independent]]'' reviewed a December 2009 episode poorly, finding it \"astonishing\" that any patients leave Holby General alive, as the staff are \"so busy looking stricken or lovelorn at each other\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/last-nights-television--holby-city-bbc1-the-many-faces-of-june-whitfield-bbc2-1852733.html|title=Last Night's Television \u2013 Holby City, BBC1; The Many Faces of June Whitfield, BBC2|last=Sutcliffe|first=Tom|date=30 December 2009|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=30 January 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102101010/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/last-nights-television--holby-city-bbc1-the-many-faces-of-june-whitfield-bbc2-1852733.html|archivedate=2 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2003, [[Libby Purves]] wrote a critical opinion piece in ''[[The Times]]'', observing that ''Holby City''{{'s}} medical staff are often depicted getting drunk in clubs, but afterwards are able to function properly at work, and that as a result, alcohol \"is made to look innocent\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/libby_purves/article840498.ece|title=My name is television and I'm an alcoholic|last=Purves|first=Libby|date=30 December 2003|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001510/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/libby_purves/article840498.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2004, Canon [[Kenyon Wright]], chair of Alcohol Focus Scotland, criticised an episode of ''Holby City'' which saw doctors downing [[tequila]] slammers, stating that it glamorised irresponsible drinking.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article501123.ece|title=Canon attacks soaps for fostering binge-drinking|last=Macaskill|first=Mark|date=31 October 2004|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001522/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article501123.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Similarly, in October 2007, drinks' industry body the [[Portman Group]] made an official complaint to communications regulator [[Ofcom]] about a scene in ''Holby City'' which depicted two medics drinking five shots of tequila following a stressful day at work. The body's chief executive David Poley claimed that in failing to show the negative consequences of this action, the series was presenting a \"highly irresponsible portrayal of excessive and rapid drinking\".<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|author=Mark Sweney|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/oct/04/bbc.television|title=Holby criticised for binge drinking scene|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=4 October 2007|accessdate=5 October 2007|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204054158/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/oct/04/bbc.television|archivedate=4 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Ofcom received a total of eight complaints about the incident.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news|author=Nicole Martin|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1565054/BBCs-Holby-City-criticised-for-binge-drinking.html|title=BBC's Holby City criticised for binge drinking|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=4 October 2007|accessdate=4 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604192504/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1565054/BBCs-Holby-City-criticised-for-binge-drinking.html|archivedate=4 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n''Holby City'' has also been accused of medical inaccuracies. The [[British Medical Association]] denounced a January 2004 episode of the serial which portrayed [[organ donation]] being carried out despite withdrawal of consent by the patient's relatives. Dr Michael Wilks, chairman of the Medical Ethics Committee stated: \"This simply would not happen, but its portrayal, even in a drama, is totally irresponsible and risks causing huge damage to the already struggling transplant programme.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1000105.ece|title=Transplant man has four kidneys|last=Hawkes|first=Nigel|date=22 January 2004|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001357/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1000105.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The British Medical Association later opined that the show was giving viewers an unrealistic impression of resuscitation by typically presenting only two outcomes, death or total recovery. Andrew Thomson, a [[Dundee]] GP, deemed this \"a terrible distortion of the truth.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article538833.ece|title=ER heroes give false recovery hopes to patients|last=Lister|first=Sam|date=30 June 2005|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001553/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article538833.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In a follow-up story for ''The Times'', Vivienne Parry highlighted the fact that in reality, less than half of patients who require resuscitation survive the initial catastrophe and only a third of those live to leave hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/health/article539089.ece|title=Well scrubbed|last=Parry|first=Vivienne|date=2 July 2009|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001603/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/health/article539089.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the [[Royal College of Nursing]] (RCN) conference in [[Bournemouth]] in April 2010, ''Holby City'' was accused of fostering unrealistic expectations of the NHS, encouraging patients to believe in miracles and fuelling compensation culture. [[Accident and emergency|Accident and Emergency]] nurse John Hill stated: \"In A&E it is sometimes a fact that sadly we cannot get people through the trauma they have received. Unfortunately, unlike in ''Holby City'', I am a mere mortal and cannot perform miracles. But many relatives believe because of that, you can. And the injury lawyers assure them that if you don't they will get recompense for it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.scotsman.com/health/TV-blamed-for-payout-culture.6257703.jp|title=TV blamed for pay-out culture|date=28 April 2010|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=19 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8647069.stm|title=Litigation and high patient expectations 'bar nursing'|last=Triggle|first=Nick|date=27 April 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=19 June 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430181611/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8647069.stm|archivedate=30 April 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Impact===\nIn October 2000, Dr John Ryan, an [[Accident & Emergency]] consultant at the [[Royal Sussex County Hospital]] in [[Brighton]] criticised the number of patients visiting the department for minor ailments without first contacting their [[general practitioner|GP]]. Ryan attributed this phenomenon to patients viewing ''Holby City'' and American medical drama ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', and falsely perceiving hospitals as glamorous.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/health/article987369.ece|title=George Clooney is not at the local A&E|last=Chaudhuri|first=Anita|date=10 October 2000|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001233/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/health/article987369.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A three-year Belgian research project, presented at a [[British Psychological Society]] meeting in September 2008, claimed that watching ''Holby City'' and similar medical dramas such as ''Casualty'' and ''ER'' had a subliminal influence on fear of illness. 1,300 teenagers were questioned on their viewing habits, and those who watched more medical dramas were found to be up to 10% more fearful about their health, with females more affected than males. Dr Jan Van Mierlo of [[Hasselt University]] stated that further research was needed into the long-term impact of television.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/7607755.stm|title=Medical TV 'feeds health fears'|date=10 September 2008|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915070336/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/7607755.stm|archivedate=15 September 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] strategists identified four archetypes based on TV programmes to help the party target [[swing voter]]s. Alongside \"''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' man\", \"''[[The Apprentice (TV series)|Apprentice]]'' generation\" and \"''[[Grand Designs]]'' couple\", they identified \"''Holby City'' worker\", a middle-ranking health service employee.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3822822.ece|title=Time for verdict on the political X-Factor|last=Oliver|first=Jonathan|author2=Watt, Holly|date=27 April 2008|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001622/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3822822.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The following year, strategists identified \"[[Holby City woman|''Holby City'' woman]]\" as a key voter demographic who may help the party win the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]]. The \"''Holby City'' woman\" is a female voter in her 30s or 40s, employed in a clinical or clerical position or some other public sector job.<ref name=\"timesonline2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/david_aaronovitch/article6729598.ece |title=Can Tories win over Holby Woman?|first=David|last= Aaronovitch|work=[[The Times]]|location=London |date= 28 July 2009|accessdate=8 August 2009}}</ref> She is a swing voter in General Elections,<ref name=\"walesonline2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/08/03/four-famous-voter-stereotypes-91466-24299536/ |title=News \u2013 Wales News \u2013 Four famous voter stereotypes |first=Tomos |last=Livingstone |work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]] |accessdate=8 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805110816/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/08/03/four-famous-voter-stereotypes-91466-24299536/ |archivedate=5 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> who has voted for the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in previous elections, though her identification with the Labour Party is not strong.<ref name=\"walesonline1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/08/03/tories-hope-holby-city-woman-will-clinch-the-next-general-election-for-them-91466-24299538/ |title=Tories hope Holby City Woman will clinch the next General Election for them |first=Tomos |last=Livingstone |work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]] |accessdate=8 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805110823/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/2009/08/03/tories-hope-holby-city-woman-will-clinch-the-next-general-election-for-them-91466-24299538/ |archivedate=5 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The \"''Holby City'' woman\" archetype is modelled on the character of [[Faye Morton]].<ref name=\"walesonline2\"/>\n\nIn January 2009, Jill Berry, president of the [[Girls' Schools Association]] and head teacher at the [[Dame Alice Harpur School]] in Bedford, cited medical dramas such as ''Holby City'' as an inspiring force in increasing numbers of female students deciding to pursue careers in medicine. Berry said: \"The girls see that as an exciting and dynamic way of life. They see it as making a difference to people's lives. It gives them a sense sometimes of the pressures, responsibility and adrenaline. Such TV programmes can be good, as long as they give a realistic impression.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/article5500698.ece|title=Hospital dramas inspire girls to do medicine|last=Woolcock|first=Nicola|date=12 January 2009|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001847/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/article5500698.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Similarly, consultant surgeon Andrew Raftery uses clips from ''Holby City'' as part of the [[University of Sheffield]] Outreach and Access to Medicine Scheme, to inspire pupils from under-represented social and educational backgrounds to pursue careers in medicine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/education/2895691.stm|title=Is there a doctor in your house?|last=Baker|first=Mike|date=29 March 2003|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507192754/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/education/2895691.stm|archivedate=7 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Holby City}}\n''Holby City'' has been nominated for over 100 awards, of which it has won six. The series has received five nominations for the [[British Academy Television Awards]], winning one. Minkie Spiro was nominated for the \"Best New Director (Fiction)\" award in 2003 for her work on the series. The show itself was nominated for the \"Best Continuing Drama\" award in 2004, 2005 and 2006, winning in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards-database.html?sq=Holby+City|title=Awards Database |publisher=[[British Academy Television Awards]]|accessdate=5 March 2010}}</ref> McHale commented on the win: \"It's fantastic not being the bridesmaid\", hoping that the award would help to make the serial \"less of a guilty pleasure\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7357516.stm|title=Brucie's big night at TV awards|last=Osborn|first=Michael|date=20 April 2008|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 August 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430054649/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7357516.stm|archivedate=30 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Holby City'' received multiple BBC Drama Award nominations between 2002 and 2006. Its best results saw the show voted fifth \"Best Drama\" in 2004 and 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2004/best_drama.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Drama \u2013 Best of 2004 \u2013 Best Drama|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807035943/http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2004/best_drama.shtml|archivedate=7 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2006/best_drama.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Drama \u2013 Best of 2006 \u2013 Best Drama|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029072830/http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2006/best_drama.shtml|archivedate=29 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Amanda Mealing]] was voted fourth \"Best Actress\" in 2006 for her role as [[Connie Beauchamp]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2006/best_actor.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Drama \u2013 Best of 2006 \u2013 Best Actor|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029105512/http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2006/best_actor.shtml|archivedate=29 October 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the \"''[[Casualty@Holby City]]''\" moment where doctor Jim Brodie ([[Maxwell Caulfield]]) sacrifices his life for midwife [[Rosie Sattar]] ([[Kim Vithana]]) was voted viewers' fourth \"Favourite Moment\" of 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2004/favourite_moment.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Drama \u2013 Best of 2004 \u2013 Favourite Moment|publisher=BBC|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903191458/http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/bestof2004/favourite_moment.shtml|archivedate=3 September 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The series has been nominated for the \"Best Drama\" award at the [[Inside Soap Awards|''Inside Soap'' Awards]] on six occasions\u2014in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/whats-on-coventry-warwickshire/tm_objectid=14693586&method=full&siteid=50003&headline=corrie-stars-in-a-lather-name_page.html |title=Corrie stars in a lather |date=28 September 2004 |work=[[Coventry Telegraph]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313092105/http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/whats-on-coventry-warwickshire/tm_objectid%3D14693586%26method%3Dfull%26siteid%3D50003%26headline%3Dcorrie-stars-in-a-lather-name_page.html |archivedate=13 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> then concurrently from 2006 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holby.tv/cgi-bin/News/fullnews.cgi?newsid1152551371,14032, |title=National TV Awards 2006 |date=10 July 2006 |work=Holby Gazette |accessdate=18 July 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/scoop/a64083/inside-soap-awards-2007-the-nominations.html |title=Inside Soap Awards 2007: The Nominations |first=Kris |last=Green |date=3 July 2007 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tkjn0kZE?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/scoop/a64083/inside-soap-awards-2007-the-nominations.html |archivedate=25 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.talkbackthames.tv/?s=news&b=29&abc=710 |title=The Bill triumphs at Inside Soap Awards |date=30 September 2008 |publisher=[[Talkback Thames]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927145222/http://www.talkbackthames.tv/?s=news&b=29&abc=710 |archivedate=27 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2009/09/22/eastender-eyes-best-actress-gong-for-fourth-year-91466-24749926/ |title=EastEnder eyes best actress gong for fourth year |date=22 September 2009 |work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 |location=Cardiff, Wales |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121011041400/http://www.walesonline.co.uk/showbiz-and-lifestyle/showbiz/2009/09/22/eastender-eyes-best-actress-gong-for-fourth-year-91466-24749926/ |archivedate=11 October 2012 |df= }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a242852/in-full-inside-soap-awards-2010-nominees.html |title=In Full: Inside Soap Awards 2010 Nominees |last=Wightman |first=Catriona |date=13 July 2010 |work=[[Digital Spy]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5tnmLsrY5?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a242852/in-full-inside-soap-awards-2010-nominees.html |archivedate=27 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n''Holby City'' has received multiple long-list nominations at the [[National Television Awards]] (NTAs) and ''[[TV Choice]]'' Awards. Mealing was short-listed for the \"Most Popular Newcomer\" award at the 2005 NTAs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://showbiz.sky.com/National-TV-Awards-Nominations |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100207002345/http://showbiz.sky.com/National-TV-Awards-Nominations |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 February 2010 |title=National TV Awards: Nominations |date=11 October 2005 |work=[[British Sky Broadcasting]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 }}</ref> and for the \"Best Actress\" award at the 2008 ''TV Choice'' Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs-old/celebs-front-page/2008/06/25/tvquick-and-tvchoice-award-nominations-announced-115875-20620559/|title=TVQuick and TVChoice Award nominations announced|first=Beth|last=Hardie|date=25 June 2008|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref> At the 2000 [[Royal Television Society Award]]s, Sean De Sparengo and Richard Gort were nominated for the \"Best Graphic Design \u2013 Titles\" award for their contribution to the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/Info_page_two_pic_2_det.asp?art_id=6961&sec_id=3506 |title=RTS Craft and Design Awards 1999\u201300 |publisher=[[Royal Television Society]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001050926/http://www.rts.org.uk/Info_page_two_pic_2_det.asp?art_id=6961&sec_id=3506 |archivedate=1 October 2010 }}</ref> The show itself was nominated in the \"Soap and Continuing Drama\" category at the 2007 awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.org.uk/Info_page_two_pic_2_det.asp?id=6940&sec_id=3476 |title=Programme Awards Winners 2007 |publisher=[[Royal Television Society]] |accessdate=18 July 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> ''Holby City'' was nominated \"Best Serial Drama\" at the 2008 [[Digital Spy Soap Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a92054/digital-spy-soap-awards-2008-the-winners.html|title=Digital Spy Soap Awards 2008: The Winners|first=Kris|last=Green|date=21 March 2008|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uHYjrB4f?url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/soaps/news/a92054/digital-spy-soap-awards-2008-the-winners.html|archivedate=16 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and in 2009, [[Stella Gonet]] was nominated for the \"Acting Performance in TV (Female)\" award at the [[BAFTA Scotland#British Academy Scotland Awards|British Academy Scotland Awards]] for her role as CEO [[Jayne Grayson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/scotland/awards/awards-report-2009,1145,BA.html|title=BAFTA Scotland Awards \u2013 The Highlights|date=23 November 2009|publisher=[[BAFTA Scotland]]|accessdate=18 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100822033333/http://www.bafta.org/scotland/awards/awards-report-2009%2C1145%2CBA.html|archivedate=22 August 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2010, the series was shortlisted in the \"Best Television Continuing Drama\" category at the [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writersguild.org.uk/public/003_WritersGuil/472_WGGBNewsGui.html |title=Writers' Guild Awards 2010 \u2013 shortlists announced |publisher=[[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] |accessdate=18 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104020406/http://www.writersguild.org.uk/public/003_WritersGuil/472_WGGBNewsGui.html |archivedate=4 November 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Ethnic Multicultural Media Academy|Ethnic Multicultural Media Awards]], [[Angela Griffin]] won \"Best Actress\" in 2000 for her role as nurse [[Jasmine Hopkins]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/may/23/britishidentity.race|title=Multiculture awards honour Mandela, Ali G and Guardian|last=Wells|first=Matt|date=23 May 2000|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=24 April 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824151105/http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/may/23/britishidentity.race|archivedate=24 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and was nominated \"Best TV Actress\" in 2002, alongside co-star [[Thusitha Jayasundera]] for her role as registrar [[Tash Bandara]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=83506|title=EMMA Awards Judges select 2002 finalists in honour of EMMA Patron Donald Woods|agency=PR Newswire|accessdate=18 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608192129/http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=83506|archivedate=8 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2004, [[Art Malik]] won the \"Best TV Actor\" award for his role as anaesthetist [[Zubin Khan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3743853.stm|title=\"Passion\" Wins EMMA Media Awards|date=25 May 2004|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 March 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721103921/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3743853.stm|archivedate=21 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nirpal Singh Dhaliwal of ''The Times'' criticised Malik's award, opining that: \"A show such as ''Holby City'' doesn't merit any recognition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/guest_contributors/article381624.ece|title=Gosh, brown and talented? Super|last=Singh Dhaliwal|first=Nirpal|date=16 April 2005|work=[[The Times]]|accessdate=5 March 2010|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605001535/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/guest_contributors/article381624.ece|archivedate=5 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The show has won three [[Screen Nation]] Awards, and received nominations for a further seven. [[Jaye Jacobs]] won the \"Emerging Talent\" award in 2005 for her role as nurse [[Donna Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screennation.co.uk/main.html |title=Screen Nation Awards 2005: And the winners are... |work=[[Screen Nation]] |accessdate=19 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100727045117/http://www.screennation.co.uk/main.html |archivedate=27 July 2010 }}</ref> In 2006, [[Rakie Ayola]] and [[Hugh Quarshie]] were nominated for the Female and Male \"Performance in TV\" awards for their roles as [[Kyla Tyson]] and [[Ric Griffin]] respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5278544.stm|title=Crash leads Screen Nation's nods|date=23 August 2006|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104212947/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/5278544.stm|archivedate=4 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holby.tv/cgi-bin/News/fullnews.cgi?newsid1156522579,14304, |title=Screen Nation Awards |date=25 August 2006 |work=Holby Gazette |accessdate=19 July 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> [[Sharon D. Clarke]] won the 2007 \"Female Performance in TV\" award for her role as [[Lola Griffin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screennation.co.uk/pdf/ScreenNation2007WinnerList.pdf |title=Screen Nation Film & TV Awards 2007 Official Winners List |work=[[Screen Nation]] |accessdate=19 July 2010 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327130458/http://www.screennation.co.uk/pdf/ScreenNation2007WinnerList.pdf |archivedate=27 March 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> while [[Ginny Holder]] was nominated in the same category for her role as [[Thandie Abebe]], and Ayola received an Honourable Mention.<ref name=\"SN2007\">{{cite web|url=http://viewer.zmags.co.uk/showmag.php?mid=gddrf#/page4/ |title=Screen Nation Awards Nominations 2007 |work=[[Screen Nation]] |pages=36\u20137 |accessdate=19 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110901134544/http://viewer.zmags.co.uk/showmag.php?mid=gddrf |archivedate=1 September 2011 |df= }}</ref> Also in 2007, [[Roger Griffiths]] was nominated for the \"Male Performance in TV\" award for his role as Harvey Tyson, and Quarshie received an Honourable Mention in the same category.<ref name=\"SN2007\"/> Quarshie went on to win \"Favourite Male TV Star\" in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screennation.co.uk/pdf/Screen-Nation-Awards-OFFICIAL-WINNERS-RELEASE-feb-09.pdf |title=Screen Nation Awards Reveals Winners for 2009 Award Show |work=[[Screen Nation]] |accessdate=19 July 2010 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728021645/http://www.screennation.co.uk/pdf/Screen-Nation-Awards-OFFICIAL-WINNERS-RELEASE-feb-09.pdf |archivedate=28 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> Also in 2008, Jacobs was nominated for the \"Favourite Female TV Star\" award, Ayola was nominated in the \"Female Performance in TV\" category, and the show itself was nominated for the \"Diversity in Drama Production\" award.<ref name=\"2008SN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourmag.co.uk/screen-nation-nominations-announced/|title=Screen Nation nominations announced|last=Allen|first=Annika|date=3 November 2008|work=[[Flavour Magazine]]|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110916211356/http://www.flavourmag.co.uk/screen-nation-nominations-announced/|archivedate=16 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center\"\n|- style=\"background:#e0e0e0;\"\n! | Series\n! | Episodes\n! | Premiere\n! | Finale\n! | Viewers<br />(in millions)\n! | Notes\n|-\n! [[Holby City (series 1)|1]]\n| 9\n| {{Start date|1999|01|12|df=y}}\n| {{Start date|1999|03|09|df=y}}\n! 9.24<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30?|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes: Week Ending 17 Jan 1999\u201314 Mar 1999|accessdate=8 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wSLX6Azh?url=http://www.barb.co.uk/report/weeklyTopProgrammesOverview|archivedate=13 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n! [[Holby City (series 2)|2]]\n| 16\n| {{Start date|1999|11|25|df=y}}\n| {{Start date|2000|03|09|df=y}}\n! 8.98<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30?|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes: Week Ending 28 Nov 1999\u201312 Mar 2000|accessdate=8 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wSLX6Azh?url=http://www.barb.co.uk/report/weeklyTopProgrammesOverview|archivedate=13 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n! [[Holby City (series 3)|3]]\n| 30\n| {{Start date|2000|10|05|df=y}}\n| {{Start date|2001|06|05|df=y}}\n! 7.75<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30?|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes: Week Ending 8 Oct 2000\u201310 Jun 2001|accessdate=8 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wSLX6Azh?url=http://www.barb.co.uk/report/weeklyTopProgrammesOverview|archivedate=13 February 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| {{refn|Final viewership data is unavailable for two episodes from series three. Episode six, \"Moving On\", recorded an overnight rating of 5.65&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/ratings-week-ending-26-november-peak-practice-overtakes-casualty-after-slow-start/1206913.article|title=Ratings: Week ending 26 November \u2013 Peak Practice overtakes Casualty after slow start|date=15 December 2000|work=[[Broadcast (magazine)|Broadcast]]|publisher=[[EMAP]]|accessdate=9 November 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001085525/http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/multi-platform/news/ratings-week-ending-26-november-peak-practice-overtakes-casualty-after-slow-start/1206913.article|archivedate=1 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> however was not among the 30 most viewed programmes on BBC One in the week of broadcast. As such, a final rating is not recorded by the [[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] (BARB). The following episode, \"The Trouble With the Truth\" also fell below the top 30. The series' average viewership is therefore calculated based on the remaining 28 episodes.|group=nb}}\n|-\n! [[Holby City (series 4)|4]]\n| 52\n| {{Start date|2001|10|09|df=y}}\n| {{Start date|2002|10|01|df=y}}\n! 7.51<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30?|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes: 